# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: photolithography
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The photons of ultraviolet have greater energy than those of visible light, from about 3.1 to 12 electron volts, around the minimum energy required to ionize atoms.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Although long-wavelength ultraviolet is not considered an ionizing radiation because its photons lack sufficient energy, it can induce chemical reactions and cause many substances to glow or fluoresce.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Many practical applications, including chemical and biological effects, are derived from the way that UV radiation can interact with organic molecules.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] These interactions can involve exciting orbital electrons to higher energy states in molecules potentially breaking chemical bonds.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In contrast, the main effect of longer wavelength radiation is to excite vibrational or rotational states of these molecules, increasing their temperature.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Short-wave ultraviolet light is ionizing radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Consequently, short-wave UV damages DNA and sterilizes surfaces with which it comes into contact.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] For humans, suntan and sunburn are familiar effects of exposure of the skin to UV, along with an increased risk of skin cancer.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The amount of UV radiation produced by the Sun means that the Earth would not be able to sustain life on dry land if most of that light were not filtered out by the atmosphere.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] More energetic, shorter-wavelength "extreme" UV below 121 nm ionizes air so strongly that it is absorbed before it reaches the ground.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] However, UV (specifically, UVB) is also responsible for the formation of vitamin D in most land vertebrates, including humans.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The UV spectrum, thus, has effects both beneficial and detrimental to life.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The lower wavelength limit of the visible spectrum is conventionally taken as 400 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Although ultraviolet rays are not generally visible to humans, 400 nm is not a sharp cutoff, with shorter and shorter wavelengths becoming less and less visible in this range.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Insects, birds, and some mammals can see near-UV (NUV), because they can see somewhat shorter wavelengths than what humans can see.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Humans generally cannot use ultraviolet rays for vision.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The lens of the human eye and surgically implanted lenses produced since 1986 block most radiation in the near UV wavelength range of 300–400 nm; shorter wavelengths are blocked by the cornea.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Humans also lack color receptor adaptations for ultraviolet rays.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The photoreceptors of the retina are sensitive to near-UV but the lens does not focus this light properly, causing UV light bulbs to look fuzzy.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] People lacking a lens (a condition known as aphakia) perceive near-UV as whitish-blue or whitish-violet.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Near-UV radiation is visible to insects, some mammals, and some birds.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Birds have a fourth color receptor for ultraviolet rays; this, coupled with eye structures that transmit more UV gives smaller birds "true" UV vision.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] "Ultraviolet" means "beyond violet" (from Latin *ultra*, "beyond"), violet being the color of the highest frequencies of visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet has a higher frequency (thus a shorter wavelength) than violet light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV radiation was discovered in February 1801 when the German physicist Johann Wilhelm Ritter observed that invisible rays just beyond the violet end of the visible spectrum darkened silver chloride-soaked paper more quickly than violet light itself.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The simpler term "chemical rays" was adopted soon afterwards, and remained popular throughout the 19th century, although some said that this radiation was entirely different from light (notably John William Draper, who named them "tithonic rays").
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The terms "chemical rays" and "heat rays" were eventually dropped in favor of ultraviolet and infrared radiation, respectively.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In 1878, the sterilizing effect of short-wavelength light by killing bacteria was discovered.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] By 1903, the most effective wavelengths were known to be around 250 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In 1960, the effect of ultraviolet radiation on DNA was established.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The discovery of the ultraviolet radiation with wavelengths below 200 nm, named "vacuum ultraviolet" because it is strongly absorbed by the oxygen in air, was made in 1893 by German physicist Victor Schumann.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The division of UV into UVA, UVB, and UVC was decided "unanimously" by a committee of the Second International Congress on Light on 17 August 1932, at the Castle of Christiansborg in Copenhagen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Several solid-state and vacuum devices have been explored for use in different parts of the UV spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Many approaches seek to adapt visible light-sensing devices, but these can suffer from unwanted response to visible light and various instabilities.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet can be detected by suitable photodiodes and photocathodes, which can be tailored to be sensitive to different parts of the UV spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Sensitive UV photomultipliers are available.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Spectrometers and radiometers are made for measurement of UV radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Silicon detectors are used across the spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Vacuum UV, or VUV, wavelengths (shorter than 200 nm) are strongly absorbed by molecular oxygen in the air, though the longer wavelengths around 150–200 nm can propagate through nitrogen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Scientific instruments can, therefore, use this spectral range by operating in an oxygen-free atmosphere (pure nitrogen, or argon for shorter wavelengths), without the need for costly vacuum chambers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Significant examples include 193-nm photolithography equipment (for semiconductor manufacturing) and circular dichroism spectrometers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Technology for VUV instrumentation was largely driven by solar astronomy for many decades.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] While optics can be used to remove unwanted visible light that contaminates the VUV, in general, detectors can be limited by their response to non-VUV radiation, and the development of solar-blind devices has been an important area of research.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Wide-gap solid-state devices or vacuum devices with high-cutoff photocathodes can be attractive compared to silicon diodes.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Extreme UV (EUV or sometimes XUV) is characterized by a transition in the physics of interaction with matter.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Wavelengths longer than about 30 nm interact mainly with the outer valence electrons of atoms, while wavelengths shorter than that interact mainly with inner-shell electrons and nuclei.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The long end of the EUV spectrum is set by a prominent He+ spectral line at 30.4 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] EUV is strongly absorbed by most known materials, but synthesizing multilayer optics that reflect up to about 50% of EUV radiation at normal incidence is possible.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This technology was pioneered by the NIXT and MSSTA sounding rockets in the 1990s, and it has been used to make telescopes for solar imaging.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] See also the Extreme Ultraviolet Explorer satellite.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Some sources use the distinction of "hard UV" and "soft UV".
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] For instance, in the case of astrophysics, the boundary may be at the Lyman limit (wavelength 91.2 nm, the energy needed to ionise a hydrogen atom from its ground state), with "hard UV" being more energetic; the same terms may also be used in other fields, such as cosmetology, optoelectronic, etc.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The numerical values of the boundary between hard/soft, even within similar scientific fields, do not necessarily coincide; for example, one applied-physics publication used a boundary of 190 nm between hard and soft UV regions.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Very hot objects emit UV radiation (see black-body radiation).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The Sun emits ultraviolet radiation at all wavelengths, including the extreme ultraviolet where it crosses into X-rays at 10 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Extremely hot stars (such as O- and B-type) emit proportionally more UV radiation than the Sun.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Sunlight in space at the top of Earth's atmosphere (see solar constant) is composed of about 50% infrared light, 40% visible light, and 10% ultraviolet light, for a total intensity of about 1400 W/m2 in vacuum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The atmosphere blocks about 77% of the Sun's UV, when the Sun is highest in the sky (at zenith), with absorption increasing at shorter UV wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] At ground level with the sun at zenith, sunlight is 44% visible light, 3% ultraviolet, and the remainder infrared.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Of the ultraviolet radiation that reaches the Earth's surface, more than 95% is the longer wavelengths of UVA, with the small remainder UVB.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Almost no UVC reaches the Earth's surface.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The fraction of UVA and UVB which remains in UV radiation after passing through the atmosphere is heavily dependent on cloud cover and atmospheric conditions.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] On "partly cloudy" days, patches of blue sky showing between clouds are also sources of (scattered) UVA and UVB, which are produced by Rayleigh scattering in the same way as the visible blue light from those parts of the sky.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB also plays a major role in plant development, as it affects most of the plant hormones.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] During total overcast, the amount of absorption due to clouds is heavily dependent on the thickness of the clouds and latitude, with no clear measurements correlating specific thickness and absorption of UVA and UVB.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The shorter bands of UVC, as well as even more-energetic UV radiation produced by the Sun, are absorbed by oxygen and generate the ozone in the ozone layer when single oxygen atoms produced by UV photolysis of dioxygen react with more dioxygen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The ozone layer is especially important in blocking most UVB and the remaining part of UVC not already blocked by ordinary oxygen in air.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet absorbers are molecules used in organic materials (polymers, paints, etc.) to absorb UV radiation to reduce the UV degradation (photo-oxidation) of a material.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The absorbers can themselves degrade over time, so monitoring of absorber levels in weathered materials is necessary.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In sunscreen, ingredients that absorb UVA/UVB rays, such as avobenzone, oxybenzone and octyl methoxycinnamate, are organic chemical absorbers or "blockers".
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] They are contrasted with inorganic absorbers/"blockers" of UV radiation such as titanium dioxide and zinc oxide.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] For clothing, the ultraviolet protection factor (UPF) represents the ratio of sunburn-causing UV without and with the protection of the fabric, similar to sun protection factor (SPF) ratings for sunscreen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Standard summer fabrics have UPFs around 6, which means that about 20% of UV will pass through.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Suspended nanoparticles in stained-glass prevent UV rays from causing chemical reactions that change image colors.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] A set of stained-glass color-reference chips is planned to be used to calibrate the color cameras for the 2019 ESA Mars rover mission, since they will remain unfaded by the high level of UV present at the surface of Mars.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Common soda–lime glass, such as window glass, is partially transparent to UVA, but is opaque to shorter wavelengths, passing about 90% of the light above 350 nm, but blocking over 90% of the light below 300 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] A study found that car windows allow 3–4% of ambient UV to pass through, especially if the UV was greater than 380 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Other types of car windows can reduce transmission of UV that is greater than 335 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Fused quartz, depending on quality, can be transparent even to vacuum UV wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Crystalline quartz and some crystals such as CaF2 and MgF2 transmit well down to 150 nm or 160 nm wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Wood's glass is a deep violet-blue barium-sodium silicate glass with about 9% nickel(II) oxide developed during World War I to block visible light for covert communications.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] It allows both infrared daylight and ultraviolet night-time communications by being transparent between 320 nm and 400 nm and also the longer infrared and far-red light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Its maximum UV transmission is at 365 nm, one of the wavelengths of mercury lamps.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Two black light fluorescent tubes, showing use.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] watt tube, shown in the bottom image in a standard plug-in fluorescent fixture.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] watt tube, used in a portable battery-powered black light sold as a pet urine detector.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] A *black light* lamp emits long-wave UVA radiation and little visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Fluorescent black light lamps work similarly to other fluorescent lamps, but use a phosphor on the inner tube surface which emits UVA radiation instead of visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Some lamps use a deep-bluish-purple Wood's glass optical filter that blocks almost all visible light with wavelengths longer than 400 nanometers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The purple glow given off by these tubes is not the ultraviolet itself, but visible purple light from mercury's 404 nm spectral line which escapes being filtered out by the coating.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Other black lights use plain glass instead of the more expensive Wood's glass, so they appear light-blue to the eye when operating.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Incandescent black lights are also produced, using a filter coating on the envelope of an incandescent bulb that absorbs visible light (*see section below*).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] These are cheaper but very inefficient, emitting only a small fraction of a percent of their power as UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Some Mercury-vapor black lights use an envelope of Wood's glass which strongly absorbs visible light while transmitting UV-A.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Black lights are used in applications in which extraneous visible light must be minimized; mainly to observe *fluorescence*, the colored glow that many substances give off when exposed to UV light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVA / UVB emitting bulbs are also sold for other special purposes, such as tanning lamps and reptile-husbandry.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Mercury-vapor lamps consisting of fused quartz tubes filled with mercury and Argon, emit ultraviolet light with two peaks in the UVC band at 253.7 nm and 185 nm as well as some visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] From 85% to 90% of the UV produced by these lamps is at 253.7 nm which very effective as a germicide.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The lamps also produce UV at 185 nm effective in producing ozone with additional germicide effects.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Such tubes have two or three times the UVC power of a regular fluorescent lamp tube.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] These low-pressure lamps have a typical efficiency of approximately 30–40%, meaning that for every 100 watts of electricity consumed by the lamp, they will produce approximately 30–40 watts of total UV output.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] They also emit bluish-white visible light, due to mercury's other spectral lines.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] These "germicidal" lamps are used extensively for disinfection of surfaces in laboratories and food-processing industries.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] 'Black light' incandescent lamps are also made from an incandescent light bulb with a filter coating which absorbs most visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Halogen lamps with fused quartz envelopes are used as inexpensive UV light sources in the near UV range, from 400 to 300 nm, in some scientific instruments.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Due to its black-body spectrum a filament light bulb is a very inefficient ultraviolet source, emitting only a fraction of a percent of its energy as UV, as explained by the black body spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Specialized UV gas-discharge lamps containing different gases produce UV radiation at particular spectral lines for scientific purposes.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Argon and deuterium arc lamps are often used as stable sources, either windowless or with various windows such as magnesium fluoride.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] These are often the emitting sources in UV spectroscopy equipment for chemical analysis.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Other UV sources with more continuous emission spectra include xenon arc lamps (commonly used as sunlight simulators), deuterium arc lamps, mercury-xenon arc lamps, and metal-halide arc lamps.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Light-emitting diodes (LEDs) can be manufactured to emit radiation in the ultraviolet range.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In 2019, following significant advances over the preceding five years, UVA LEDs of 365 nm and longer wavelength were available, with efficiencies of 50% at 1.0 W output.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Currently, the most common types of UV LEDs are in 395 nm and 365 nm wavelengths, both of which are in the UVA spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The rated wavelength is the peak wavelength that the LEDs put out, but both higher and lower wavelengths are present.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The cheaper and more common 395 nm UV LEDs are much closer to the visible spectrum, and give off a purple color.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Other UV LEDs deeper into the spectrum do not emit as much visible light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] LEDs are used for applications such as UV curing applications, charging glow-in-the-dark objects such as paintings or toys, and lights for detecting counterfeit money and bodily fluids.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV LEDs are also used in digital print applications and inert UV curing environments.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVC LEDs are developing rapidly, but may require testing to verify effective disinfection.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Citations for large-area disinfection are for non-LED UV sources known as germicidal lamps.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Also, they are used as line sources to replace deuterium lamps in liquid chromatography instruments.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Excimer lasers emitting in ultraviolet and vacuum ultraviolet wavelength ranges are widely used in many industries.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Argon-fluoride excimer lasers operating at 193 nm are routinely used in integrated circuit production by photolithography.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Coherent sources are available down to a wavelength limit around 126 nm, characteristic of the Ar2* excimer laser.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Direct UV-emitting laser diodes are available at 375 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV diode-pumped solid state lasers have been demonstrated using cerium-doped lithium strontium aluminum fluoride crystals (Ce:LiSAF), a process developed in the 1990s at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Wavelengths shorter than 325 nm are commercially generated in diode-pumped solid-state lasers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet lasers can also be made by applying frequency conversion to lower-frequency lasers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet lasers have applications in industry (laser engraving), medicine (dermatology, and keratectomy), chemistry (MALDI), free-space optical communication, computing (optical storage), and manufacture of integrated circuits.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The vacuum ultraviolet (V‑UV) band (100–200 nm) can be generated by non-linear 4 wave mixing in gases by sum or difference frequency mixing of 2 or more longer wavelength lasers.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The generation is generally done in gasses (e.g. krypton, hydrogen which are two-photon resonant near 193 nm) or metal vapors (e.g. magnesium).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] By making one of the lasers tunable, the V‑UV can be tuned.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] If one of the lasers is resonant with a transition in the gas or vapor then the V‑UV production is intensified.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] However, resonances also generate wavelength dispersion, and thus the phase matching can limit the tunable range of the 4 wave mixing.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Difference frequency mixing (i.e., f1 + f2 − f3) has an advantage over sum frequency mixing because the phase matching can provide greater tuning.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In particular, difference frequency mixing two photons of an ArF (193 nm) excimer laser with a tunable visible or near IR laser in hydrogen or krypton provides resonantly enhanced tunable V‑UV covering from 100 nm to 200 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Practically, the lack of suitable gas / vapor cell window materials above the lithium fluoride cut-off wavelength limit the tuning range to longer than about 110 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Tunable V‑UV wavelengths down to 75 nm was achieved using window-free configurations.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Lasers have been used to indirectly generate non-coherent extreme UV (E‑UV) radiation at 13.5 nm for extreme ultraviolet lithography.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The E‑UV is not emitted by the laser, but rather by electron transitions in an extremely hot tin or xenon plasma, which is excited by an excimer laser.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This technique does not require a synchrotron, yet can produce UV at the edge of the X‑ray spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Synchrotron light sources can also produce all wavelengths of UV, including those at the boundary of the UV and X‑ray spectra at 10 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The impact of ultraviolet radiation on human health has implications for the risks and benefits of sun exposure and is also implicated in issues such as fluorescent lamps and health.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Getting too much sun exposure can be harmful, but in moderation, sun exposure is beneficial.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV (specifically, UVB) causes the body to produce vitamin D, which is essential for life.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Humans need some UV radiation to maintain adequate vitamin D levels.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Vitamin D can also be obtained from food and supplementation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Excess sun exposure produces harmful effects, however.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV rays also treat certain skin conditions.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Modern phototherapy has been used to successfully treat psoriasis, eczema, jaundice, vitiligo, atopic dermatitis, and localized scleroderma.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In addition, UV radiation, in particular UVB radiation, has been shown to induce cell cycle arrest in keratinocytes, the most common type of skin cell.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] As such, sunlight therapy can be a candidate for treatment of conditions such as psoriasis and exfoliative cheilitis, conditions in which skin cells divide more rapidly than usual or necessary.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In humans, excessive exposure to UV radiation can result in acute and chronic harmful effects on the eye's dioptric system and retina.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The risk is elevated at high altitudes and people living in high latitude areas where snow covers the ground right into early summer and sun positions even at zenith are low, are particularly at risk.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Skin, the circadian system, and the immune system can also be affected.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The differential effects of various wavelengths of light on the human cornea and skin are sometimes called the "erythemal action spectrum".
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The action spectrum shows that UVA does not cause immediate reaction, but rather UV begins to cause photokeratitis and skin redness (with lighter skinned individuals being more sensitive) at wavelengths starting near the beginning of the UVB band at 315 nm, and rapidly increasing to 300 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The skin and eyes are most sensitive to damage by UV at 265–275 nm, which is in the lower UVC band.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] At still shorter wavelengths of UV, damage continues to happen, but the overt effects are not as great with so little penetrating the atmosphere.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The WHO-standard ultraviolet index is a widely publicized measurement of total strength of UV wavelengths that cause sunburn on human skin, by weighting UV exposure for action spectrum effects at a given time and location.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This standard shows that most sunburn happens due to UV at wavelengths near the boundary of the UVA and UVB bands.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Overexposure to UVB radiation not only can cause sunburn but also some forms of skin cancer.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] However, the degree of redness and eye irritation (which are largely not caused by UVA) do not predict the long-term effects of UV, although they do mirror the direct damage of DNA by ultraviolet.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] All bands of UV radiation damage collagen fibers and accelerate aging of the skin.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Both UVA and UVB destroy vitamin A in skin, which may cause further damage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB radiation can cause direct DNA damage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This cancer connection is one reason for concern about ozone depletion and the ozone hole.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The most deadly form of skin cancer, melanoma, is mostly caused by DNA damage independent from UVA radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This can be seen from the absence of a direct UV signature mutation in 92% of all melanoma.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Occasional overexposure and sunburn are probably greater risk factors for melanoma than long-term moderate exposure.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVC is the highest-energy, most-dangerous type of ultraviolet radiation, and causes adverse effects that can variously be mutagenic or carcinogenic.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In the past, UVA was considered not harmful or less harmful than UVB, but today it is known to contribute to skin cancer via indirect DNA damage (free radicals such as reactive oxygen species).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVA can generate highly reactive chemical intermediates, such as hydroxyl and oxygen radicals, which in turn can damage DNA.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The DNA damage caused indirectly to skin by UVA consists mostly of single-strand breaks in DNA, while the damage caused by UVB includes direct formation of thymine dimers or cytosine dimers and double-strand DNA breakage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVA is immunosuppressive for the entire body (accounting for a large part of the immunosuppressive effects of sunlight exposure), and is mutagenic for basal cell keratinocytes in skin.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB photons can cause direct DNA damage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB radiation excites DNA molecules in skin cells, causing aberrant covalent bonds to form between adjacent pyrimidine bases, producing a dimer.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Most UV-induced pyrimidine dimers in DNA are removed by the process known as nucleotide excision repair that employs about 30 different proteins.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Those pyrimidine dimers that escape this repair process can induce a form of programmed cell death (apoptosis) or can cause DNA replication errors leading to mutation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB damages mRNA This triggers a fast pathway that leads to inflammation of the skin and sunburn. mRNA damage initially triggers a response in ribosomes though a protein known as ZAK-alpha in a ribotoxic stress response.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This response acts as a cell surveillance system.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Following this detection of RNA damage leads to inflammatory signaling and recruitment of immune cells.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This, not DNA damage (which is slower to detect) results in UVB skin inflammation and acute sunburn.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] As a defense against UV radiation, the amount of the brown pigment melanin in the skin increases when exposed to moderate (depending on skin type) levels of radiation; this is commonly known as a sun tan.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The purpose of melanin is to absorb UV radiation and dissipate the energy as harmless heat, protecting the skin against both direct and indirect DNA damage from the UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVA gives a quick tan that lasts for days by oxidizing melanin that was already present and triggers the release of the melanin from melanocytes.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UVB yields a tan that takes roughly 2 days to develop because it stimulates the body to produce more melanin.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Medical organizations recommend that patients protect themselves from UV radiation by using sunscreen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Five sunscreen ingredients have been shown to protect mice against skin tumors.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] However, some sunscreen chemicals produce potentially harmful substances if they are illuminated while in contact with living cells.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The amount of sunscreen that penetrates into the lower layers of the skin may be large enough to cause damage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Sunscreen reduces the direct DNA damage that causes sunburn, by blocking UVB, and the usual SPF rating indicates how effectively this radiation is blocked.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] SPF is, therefore, also called UVB-PF, for "UVB protection factor".
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] This rating, however, offers no data about important protection against UVA, which does not primarily cause sunburn but is still harmful, since it causes indirect DNA damage and is also considered carcinogenic.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Several studies suggest that the absence of UVA filters may be the cause of the higher incidence of melanoma found in sunscreen users compared to non-users.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Some sunscreen lotions contain titanium dioxide, zinc oxide, and avobenzone, which help protect against UVA rays.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The photochemical properties of melanin make it an excellent photoprotectant.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] However, sunscreen chemicals cannot dissipate the energy of the excited state as efficiently as melanin and therefore, if sunscreen ingredients penetrate into the lower layers of the skin, the amount of reactive oxygen species may be increased.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The amount of sunscreen that penetrates through the stratum corneum may or may not be large enough to cause damage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In an experiment by Hanson *et al*. that was published in 2006, the amount of harmful reactive oxygen species (ROS) was measured in untreated and in sunscreen treated skin.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] In the first 20 minutes, the film of sunscreen had a protective effect and the number of ROS species was smaller.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] After 60 minutes, however, the amount of absorbed sunscreen was so high that the amount of ROS was higher in the sunscreen-treated skin than in the untreated skin.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The study indicates that sunscreen must be reapplied within 2 hours in order to prevent UV light from penetrating to sunscreen-infused live skin cells.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ultraviolet radiation can aggravate several skin conditions and diseases, including systemic lupus erythematosus, Sjögren's syndrome, Sinear Usher syndrome, rosacea, dermatomyositis, Darier's disease, Kindler–Weary syndrome and Porokeratosis.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The eye is most sensitive to damage by UV in the lower UVC band at 265–275 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Radiation of this wavelength is almost absent from sunlight at the surface of the Earth but is emitted by artificial sources such as the electrical arcs employed in arc welding.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Unprotected exposure to these sources can cause "welder's flash" or "arc eye" (photokeratitis) and can lead to cataracts, pterygium and pinguecula formation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] To a lesser extent, UVB in sunlight from 310 to 280 nm also causes photokeratitis ("snow blindness"), and the cornea, the lens, and the retina can be damaged.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Protective eyewear is beneficial to those exposed to ultraviolet radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Since light can reach the eyes from the sides, full-coverage eye protection is usually warranted if there is an increased risk of exposure, as in high-altitude mountaineering.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Mountaineers are exposed to higher-than-ordinary levels of UV radiation, both because there is less atmospheric filtering and because of reflection from snow and ice.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Ordinary, untreated eyeglasses give some protection.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Most plastic lenses give more protection than glass lenses, because, as noted above, glass is transparent to UVA and the common acrylic plastic used for lenses is less so.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Some plastic lens materials, such as polycarbonate, inherently block most UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV degradation is one form of polymer degradation that affects plastics exposed to sunlight.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The problem appears as discoloration or fading, cracking, loss of strength or disintegration.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The effects of attack increase with exposure time and sunlight intensity.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] The addition of UV absorbers inhibits the effect.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Sensitive polymers include thermoplastics and speciality fibers like aramids.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] UV absorption leads to chain degradation and loss of strength at sensitive points in the chain structure.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Aramid rope must be shielded with a sheath of thermoplastic if it is to retain its strength.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Many pigments and dyes absorb UV and change colour, so paintings and textiles may need extra protection both from sunlight and fluorescent lamps, two common sources of UV radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Window glass absorbs some harmful UV, but valuable artifacts need extra shielding.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Many museums place black curtains over watercolour paintings and ancient textiles, for example.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Since watercolours can have very low pigment levels, they need extra protection from UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p01] Various forms of picture framing glass, including acrylics (plexiglass), laminates, and coatings, offer different degrees of UV (and visible light) protection.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Because of its ability to cause chemical reactions and excite fluorescence in materials, ultraviolet radiation has a number of applications.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The following table gives some uses of specific wavelength bands in the UV spectrum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photographic film responds to ultraviolet radiation but the glass lenses of cameras usually block radiation shorter than 350 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Slightly yellow UV-blocking filters are often used for outdoor photography to prevent unwanted bluing and overexposure by UV rays.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] For photography in the near UV, special filters may be used.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photography with wavelengths shorter than 350 nm requires special quartz lenses which do not absorb the radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Digital cameras sensors may have internal filters that block UV to improve color rendition accuracy.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Sometimes these internal filters can be removed, or they may be absent, and an external visible-light filter prepares the camera for near-UV photography.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] A few cameras are designed for use in the UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photography by reflected ultraviolet radiation is useful for medical, scientific, and forensic investigations, in applications as widespread as detecting bruising of skin, alterations of documents, or restoration work on paintings.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photography of the fluorescence produced by ultraviolet illumination uses visible wavelengths of light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In ultraviolet astronomy, measurements are used to discern the chemical composition of the interstellar medium, and the temperature and composition of stars.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Because the ozone layer blocks many UV frequencies from reaching telescopes on the surface of the Earth, most UV observations are made from space.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Corona discharge on electrical apparatus can be detected by its ultraviolet emissions.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Corona causes degradation of electrical insulation and emission of ozone and nitrogen oxide.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] EPROMs (Erasable Programmable Read-Only Memory) are erased by exposure to UV radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] These modules have a transparent (quartz) window on the top of the chip that allows the UV radiation in.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Colorless fluorescent dyes that emit blue light under UV are added as optical brighteners to paper and fabrics.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The blue light emitted by these agents counteracts yellow tints that may be present and causes the colors and whites to appear whiter or more brightly colored.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV fluorescent dyes that glow in the primary colors are used in paints, papers, and textiles either to enhance color under daylight illumination or to provide special effects when lit with UV lamps.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Blacklight paints that contain dyes that glow under UV are used in a number of art and aesthetic applications.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] To help prevent counterfeiting of currency, or forgery of important documents such as driver's licenses and passports, the paper may include a UV watermark or fluorescent multicolor fibers that are visible under ultraviolet light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Postage stamps are tagged with a phosphor that glows under UV rays to permit automatic detection of the stamp and facing of the letter.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV fluorescent dyes are used in many applications (for example, biochemistry and forensics).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Some brands of pepper spray will leave an invisible chemical (UV dye) that is not easily washed off on a pepper-sprayed attacker, which would help police identify the attacker later.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In some types of nondestructive testing UV stimulates fluorescent dyes to highlight defects in a broad range of materials.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] These dyes may be carried into surface-breaking defects by capillary action (liquid penetrant inspection) or they may be bound to ferrite particles caught in magnetic leakage fields in ferrous materials (magnetic particle inspection).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV is an investigative tool at the crime scene helpful in locating and identifying bodily fluids such as semen, blood, and saliva.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] For example, ejaculated fluids or saliva can be detected by high-power UV sources, irrespective of the structure or colour of the surface the fluid is deposited upon.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV–vis microspectroscopy is also used to analyze trace evidence, such as textile fibers and paint chips, as well as questioned documents.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Other applications include the authentication of various collectibles and art, and detecting counterfeit currency.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Even materials not specially marked with UV sensitive dyes may have distinctive fluorescence under UV exposure or may fluoresce differently under short-wave versus long-wave ultraviolet.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Using multi-spectral imaging it is possible to read illegible papyrus, such as the burned papyri of the Villa of the Papyri or of Oxyrhynchus, or the Archimedes palimpsest.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The technique involves taking pictures of the illegible document using different filters in the infrared or ultraviolet range, finely tuned to capture certain wavelengths of light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Thus, the optimum spectral portion can be found for distinguishing ink from paper on the papyrus surface.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Simple NUV sources can be used to highlight faded iron-based ink on vellum.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet helps detect organic material deposits that remain on surfaces where periodic cleaning and sanitizing may have failed.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] It is used in the hotel industry, manufacturing, and other industries where levels of cleanliness or contamination are inspected.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Perennial news features for many television news organizations involve an investigative reporter using a similar device to reveal unsanitary conditions in hotels, public toilets, hand rails, and such.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV/Vis spectroscopy is widely used as a technique in chemistry to analyze chemical structure, the most notable one being conjugated systems.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV radiation is often used to excite a given sample where the fluorescent emission is measured with a spectrofluorometer.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In biological research, UV radiation is used for quantification of nucleic acids or proteins.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In environmental chemistry, UV radiation could also be used to detect Contaminants of emerging concern in water samples.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In pollution control applications, ultraviolet analyzers are used to detect emissions of nitrogen oxides, sulfur compounds, mercury, and ammonia, for example in the flue gas of fossil-fired power plants.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet radiation can detect thin sheens of spilled oil on water, either by the high reflectivity of oil films at UV wavelengths, fluorescence of compounds in oil, or by absorbing of UV created by Raman scattering in water.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV absorbance can also be used to quantify contaminants in wastewater.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Most commonly used 254 nm UV absorbance is generally used as a surrogate parameters to quantify NOM.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Another form of light-based detection uses an excitation-emission matrix (EEM) to detect and identify contaminants based on their fluorescence properties.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] EEM could be used to discriminate different groups of NOM based on the difference in light emission and excitation of fluorophores.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] NOMs with certain molecular structures are reported to have fluorescent properties in a wide range of excitation/emission wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet lamps are also used as part of the analysis of some minerals and gems.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In general, ultraviolet detectors use either a solid-state device, such as one based on silicon carbide or aluminium nitride, or a gas-filled tube as the sensing element.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV detectors that are sensitive to UV in any part of the spectrum respond to irradiation by sunlight and artificial light.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Virtually all fires emit some radiation in the UVC band, whereas the Sun's radiation at this band is absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The result is that the UV detector is "solar blind", meaning it will not cause an alarm in response to radiation from the Sun, so it can easily be used both indoors and outdoors.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV detectors are sensitive to most fires, including hydrocarbons, metals, sulfur, hydrogen, hydrazine, and ammonia.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Arc welding, electrical arcs, lightning, X-rays used in nondestructive metal testing equipment (though this is highly unlikely), and radioactive materials can produce levels that will activate a UV detection system.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The presence of UV-absorbing gases and vapors will attenuate the UV radiation from a fire, adversely affecting the ability of the detector to detect flames.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Likewise, the presence of an oil mist in the air or an oil film on the detector window will have the same effect.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet radiation is used for very fine resolution photolithography, a procedure wherein a chemical called a photoresist is exposed to UV radiation that has passed through a mask.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The exposure causes chemical reactions to occur in the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] After removal of unwanted photoresist, a pattern determined by the mask remains on the sample.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Steps may then be taken to "etch" away, deposit on or otherwise modify areas of the sample where no photoresist remains.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photolithography is used in the manufacture of semiconductors, integrated circuit components, and printed circuit boards.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photolithography processes used to fabricate electronic integrated circuits presently use 193 nm UV and are experimentally using 13.5 nm UV for extreme ultraviolet lithography.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Electronic components that require clear transparency for light to exit or enter (photovoltaic panels and sensors) can be potted using acrylic resins that are cured using UV energy.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The advantages are low VOC emissions and rapid curing.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Certain inks, coatings, and adhesives are formulated with photoinitiators and resins.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] When exposed to UV light, polymerization occurs, and so the adhesives harden or cure, usually within a few seconds.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Applications include glass and plastic bonding, optical fiber coatings, the coating of flooring, UV coating and paper finishes in offset printing, dental fillings, hydrophobic light-activated adhesive, and decorative fingernail "gels".
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV sources for UV curing applications include UV lamps, UV LEDs, and excimer flash lamps.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Fast processes such as flexo or offset printing require high-intensity light focused via reflectors onto a moving substrate and medium so high-pressure Hg (mercury) or Fe (iron, doped)-based bulbs are used, energized with electric arcs or microwaves.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Lower-power fluorescent lamps and LEDs can be used for static applications.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Small high-pressure lamps can have light focused and transmitted to the work area via liquid-filled or fiber-optic light guides.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The impact of UV on polymers is used for modification of the (roughness and hydrophobicity) of polymer surfaces.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] For example, a poly(methyl methacrylate) surface can be smoothed by vacuum ultraviolet.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV radiation is useful in preparing low-surface-energy polymers for adhesives.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Polymers exposed to UV will oxidize, thus raising the surface energy of the polymer.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Once the surface energy of the polymer has been raised, the bond between the adhesive and the polymer is stronger.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV-C light is used in air conditioning systems as a method of improving indoor air quality by disinfecting the air and preventing microbial growth.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV-C light is effective at killing or inactivating harmful microorganisms, such as bacteria, viruses, mold, and mildew.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] When integrated into an air conditioning system, the ultraviolet light is typically placed in areas like the air handler or near the evaporator coil.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In air conditioning systems, UV-C light works by irradiating the airflow within the system, killing or neutralizing harmful microorganisms before they are recirculated into the indoor environment.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The effectiveness of it in air conditioning systems depends on factors such as the intensity of the light, the duration of exposure, airflow speed, and the cleanliness of system components.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Using a catalytic chemical reaction from titanium dioxide and UVC exposure, oxidation of organic matter converts pathogens, pollens, and mold spores into harmless inert byproducts.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] However, the reaction of titanium dioxide and UVC is not a straight path.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Several hundreds of reactions occur prior to the inert byproducts stage and can hinder the resulting reaction creating formaldehyde, aldehyde, and other VOC's en route to a final stage.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Thus, the use of titanium dioxide and UVC requires very specific parameters for a successful outcome.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The cleansing mechanism of UV is a photochemical process.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Contaminants in the indoor environment are almost entirely organic carbon-based compounds, which break down when exposed to high-intensity UV at 240 to 280 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Short-wave ultraviolet radiation can destroy DNA in living microorganisms.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UVC's effectiveness is directly related to intensity and exposure time.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV has also been shown to reduce gaseous contaminants such as carbon monoxide and VOCs.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV lamps radiating at 184 and 254 nm can remove low concentrations of hydrocarbons and carbon monoxide if the air is recycled between the room and the lamp chamber.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] This arrangement prevents the introduction of ozone into the treated air.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Likewise, air may be treated by passing by a single UV source operating at 184 nm and passed over iron pentaoxide to remove the ozone produced by the UV lamp.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet lamps are used to sterilize workspaces and tools used in biology laboratories and medical facilities.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Commercially available low-pressure mercury-vapor lamps emit about 86% of their radiation at 254 nanometers (nm), with 265 nm being the peak germicidal effectiveness curve.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV at these germicidal wavelengths damage a microorganism's DNA/RNA so that it cannot reproduce, making it harmless, (even though the organism may not be killed).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Since microorganisms can be shielded from ultraviolet rays in small cracks and other shaded areas, these lamps are used only as a supplement to other sterilization techniques.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UVC LEDs are relatively new to the commercial market and are gaining in popularity.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Due to their monochromatic nature (±5 nm) these LEDs can target a specific wavelength needed for disinfection.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] This is especially important knowing that pathogens vary in their sensitivity to specific UV wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] LEDs are mercury free, instant on/off, and have unlimited cycling throughout the day.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Disinfection using UV radiation is commonly used in wastewater treatment applications and is finding an increased usage in municipal drinking water treatment.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many bottlers of spring water use UV disinfection equipment to sterilize their water.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Solar water disinfection has been researched for cheaply treating contaminated water using natural sunlight.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The UVA irradiation and increased water temperature kill organisms in the water.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet radiation is used in several food processes to kill unwanted microorganisms.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV can be used to pasteurize fruit juices by flowing the juice over a high-intensity ultraviolet source.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The effectiveness of such a process depends on the UV absorbance of the juice.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Pulsed light (PL) is a technique of killing microorganisms on surfaces using pulses of an intense broad spectrum, rich in UVC between 200 and 280 nm.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Pulsed light works with xenon flash lamps that can produce flashes several times per second.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UVC has also been shown to be effective at degrading SARS-CoV-2 virus.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Most birds, reptiles, insects (such as bees), and a few mammals such as mice, reindeer, dogs, and cats can see near-ultraviolet wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many fruits, flowers, and seeds stand out more strongly from the background in ultraviolet wavelengths as compared to human color vision.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Scorpions glow or take on a yellow to green color under UV illumination, thus assisting in the control of these arachnids.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Mantis Shrimp such as *Neogonodactylus oerstedii* can sense ultraviolet wavelengths assisting them in hunting and survival.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many birds have patterns in their plumage that are invisible at usual wavelengths but observable in ultraviolet, and the urine and other secretions of some animals, including dogs, cats, and human beings, are much easier to spot with ultraviolet.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Urine trails of rodents can be detected by pest control technicians for proper treatment of infested dwellings.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Butterflies use ultraviolet as a communication system for sex recognition and mating behavior.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] For example, in the *Colias eurytheme* butterfly, males rely on visual cues to locate and identify females.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Instead of using chemical stimuli to find mates, males are attracted to the ultraviolet-reflecting color of female hind wings.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] In *Pieris napi* butterflies it was shown that females in northern Finland with less UV-radiation present in the environment possessed stronger UV signals to attract their males than those occurring further south.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] This suggested that it was evolutionarily more difficult to increase the UV-sensitivity of the eyes of the males than to increase the UV-signals emitted by the females.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many insects use the ultraviolet wavelength emissions from celestial objects as references for flight navigation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] A local ultraviolet emitter will normally disrupt the navigation process and will eventually attract the flying insect.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The green fluorescent protein (GFP) is often used in genetics as a marker.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many substances, such as proteins, have significant light absorption bands in the ultraviolet that are of interest in biochemistry and related fields.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV-capable spectrophotometers are common in such laboratories.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet traps called bug zappers are used to eliminate various small flying insects.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] They are attracted to the UV and are killed using an electric shock, or trapped once they come into contact with the device.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Different designs of ultraviolet radiation traps are also used by entomologists for collecting nocturnal insects during faunistic survey studies.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Ultraviolet radiation is helpful in the treatment of skin conditions such as psoriasis and vitiligo.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Exposure to UVA, while the skin is hyper-photosensitive, by taking psoralens is an effective treatment for psoriasis.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Due to the potential of psoralens to cause damage to the liver, PUVA therapy may be used only a limited number of times over a patient's lifetime.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UVB phototherapy does not require additional medications or topical preparations for the therapeutic benefit; only the exposure is needed.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] However, phototherapy can be effective when used in conjunction with certain topical treatments such as anthralin, coal tar, and vitamin A and D derivatives, or systemic treatments such as methotrexate and Soriatane.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Reptiles need UV‑B for biosynthesis of vitamin D, and other metabolic processes.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Specifically cholecalciferol (vitamin D3), which is needed for basic cellular / neural functioning as well as the utilization of calcium for bone and egg production.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The UV‑A wavelength is also visible to many reptiles and might play a significant role in their ability survive in the wild as well as in visual communication between individuals.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Therefore, in a typical reptile enclosure, a fluorescent UV‑A / UV‑B source (at the proper spectrum strength and coverage for the species), must be available for many captive species to survive.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Simple supplementation with cholecalciferol (vitamin D3) will not be enough as there is a complete biosynthetic pathway that is metabolically "leap-frogged" (risks of possible overdoses), the intermediate molecules and metabolites also play important functions in the animals health.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Natural sunlight in the right levels is always going to be superior to artificial sources, but this might not be possible for keepers in different parts of the world.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] It is a known problem that high levels of output of the UV‑A part of the spectrum can both cause cellular and DNA damage to sensitive parts of their bodies – especially the eyes where blindness is the result of improper UV‑A and UV‑B source placement and use (an overdose is called *photokeratitis*).
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] For many keepers there must also be a provision for an adequate heat source this has resulted in the marketing of heat and light "combination" products.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] A better strategy is to use separate lamps for separate UV bands so that keepers can place and control the lamps' intensity for best animal health.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The evolution of early reproductive proteins and enzymes is attributed in modern models of evolutionary theory to ultraviolet radiation.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UVB causes thymine base pairs next to each other in genetic sequences to bond together into thymine dimers, a disruption in the strand that reproductive enzymes cannot copy.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] This leads to frameshifting during genetic replication and protein synthesis, usually killing the cell.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Before formation of the UV-blocking ozone layer, when early prokaryotes approached the surface of the ocean, they almost invariably died out.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] The few that survived had developed enzymes that monitored the genetic material and removed thymine dimers by nucleotide excision repair enzymes.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Many enzymes and proteins involved in modern mitosis and meiosis are similar to repair enzymes, and are believed to be evolved modifications of the enzymes originally used to overcome DNA damages caused by UV.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Elevated levels of ultraviolet radiation, in particular UV-B, have also been speculated as a cause of mass extinctions in the fossil record.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Photobiology is the scientific study of the beneficial and harmful interactions of non-ionizing radiation in living organisms, conventionally demarcated around 10 eV, the first ionization energy of oxygen.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] UV ranges roughly from 3 to 30 eV in energy.
[src:photolithography/deep-ultraviolet-p02] Hence photobiology entertains some, but not all, of the UV spectrum.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] For many etch steps, part of the wafer is protected from the etchant by a "masking" material which resists etching.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] In some cases, the masking material is a photoresist which has been patterned using photolithography.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Other situations require a more durable mask, such as silicon nitride.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The two fundamental types of etchants are liquid-phase ("wet") and plasma-phase ("dry").
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Each of these exists in several varieties.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The first etching processes used liquid-phase ("wet") etchants.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] This process is now largely outdated but was used up until the late 1980s when it was superseded by dry plasma etching.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The wafer can be immersed in a bath of etchant, which must be agitated to achieve good process control.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] For instance, buffered hydrofluoric acid (BHF) is used commonly to etch silicon dioxide over a silicon substrate.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Different specialized etchants can be used to characterize the surface etched.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Wet etchants are usually isotropic, which leads to a large bias when etching thick films.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] They also require the disposal of large amounts of toxic waste.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] For these reasons, they are seldom used in state-of-the-art processes.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] However, the photographic developer used for photoresist resembles wet etching.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] As an alternative to immersion, single wafer machines use the Bernoulli principle to employ a gas (usually, pure nitrogen) to cushion and protect one side of the wafer while etchant is applied to the other side.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] It can be done to either the front side or back side.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The etch chemistry is dispensed on the top side when in the machine and the bottom side is not affected.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] This etching method is particularly effective just before "backend" processing (BEOL), where wafers are normally very much thinner after wafer backgrinding, and very sensitive to thermal or mechanical stress.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Etching a thin layer of even a few micrometres will remove microcracks produced during backgrinding resulting in the wafer having dramatically increased strength and flexibility without breaking.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Some wet etchants etch crystalline materials at very different rates depending upon which crystal face is exposed.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] In single-crystal materials (e.g. silicon wafers), this effect can allow very high anisotropy, as shown in the figure.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The term "crystallographic etching" is synonymous with "anisotropic etching along crystal planes".
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] However, for some non-crystal materials like glass, there are unconventional ways to etch in an anisotropic manner.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The authors employ multistream laminar flow that contains etching non-etching solutions to fabricate a glass groove.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The etching solution at the center is flanked by non-etching solutions and the area contacting etching solutions is limited by the surrounding non-etching solutions.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The etching direction is thereby mainly vertical to the glass surface.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The scanning electron microscopy (SEM) images demonstrate the breaking of the conventional theoretical limit of aspect ratio (width/height=0.5) and contribute a two-fold improvement (width/height=1).
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Several anisotropic wet etchants are available for silicon, all of them hot aqueous caustics.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] For instance, potassium hydroxide (KOH) displays an etch rate selectivity 400 times higher in <100> crystal directions than in <111> directions.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] EDP (an aqueous solution of ethylene diamine and pyrocatechol), displays a <100>/<111> selectivity of 17X, does not etch silicon dioxide as KOH does, and also displays high selectivity between lightly doped and heavily boron-doped (p-type) silicon.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Use of these etchants on wafers that already contain CMOS integrated circuits requires protecting the circuitry.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] KOH may introduce mobile potassium ions into silicon dioxide, and EDP is highly corrosive and carcinogenic, so care is required in their use.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Tetramethylammonium hydroxide (TMAH) presents a safer alternative than EDP, with a 37X selectivity between {100} and {111} planes in silicon.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Etching a (100) silicon surface through a rectangular hole in a masking material, like a hole in a layer of silicon nitride, creates a pit with flat sloping {111}-oriented sidewalls and a flat (100)-oriented bottom.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] If the etching is continued "to completion", i.e. until the flat bottom disappears, the pit becomes a trench with a V-shaped cross-section.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] If the original rectangle was a perfect square, the pit when etched to completion displays a pyramidal shape.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] where *R*xxx is the etch rate in the <xxx> direction, *T* is the etch time, *D* is the etch depth and *S* is the anisotropy of the material and etchant.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Different etchants have different anisotropies.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Modern very large scale integration (VLSI) processes avoid wet etching, and use *plasma etching* instead.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Plasma etchers can operate in several modes by adjusting the parameters of the plasma.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Ordinary plasma etching operates between 0.1 and 5 Torr.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] (This unit of pressure, commonly used in vacuum engineering, equals approximately 133.3 pascals.) The plasma produces energetic free radicals, neutrally charged, that react at the surface of the wafer.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Since neutral particles attack the wafer from all angles, this process is isotropic.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Plasma etching can be isotropic, i.e., exhibiting a lateral undercut rate on a patterned surface approximately the same as its downward etch rate, or can be anisotropic, i.e., exhibiting a smaller lateral undercut rate than its downward etch rate.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Such anisotropy is maximized in deep reactive ion etching (DRIE).
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The use of the term anisotropy for plasma etching should not be conflated with the use of the same term when referring to orientation-dependent etching.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The source gas for the plasma usually contains small molecules rich in chlorine or fluorine.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] For instance, carbon tetrachloride (CCl4) etches silicon and aluminium, and trifluoromethane etches silicon dioxide and silicon nitride.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] A plasma containing oxygen is used to oxidize ("ash") photoresist and facilitate its removal.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] If the etch is intended to make a cavity in a material, the depth of the cavity may be controlled approximately using the etching time and the known etch rate.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] More often, though, etching must entirely remove the top layer of a multilayer structure, without damaging the underlying or masking layers.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The etching system's ability to do this depends on the ratio of etch rates in the two materials (*selectivity*).
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Some etches undercut the masking layer and form cavities with sloping sidewalls.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] The distance of undercutting is called *bias*.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Etchants with large bias are called *isotropic*, because they erode the substrate equally in all directions.
[src:photolithography/etching-microfabrication] Modern processes greatly prefer *anisotropic* etches, because they produce sharp, well-controlled features.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] As of 2025, ASML Holding is the only company that produces and sells EUV systems for chip production, targeting 5 nanometer (nm) and 3 nm process nodes, though Reuters reported in December 2025 that China had developed its own prototype EUV system.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The EUV wavelengths that are used in EUVL are near 13.5 nanometers (nm), using a laser-pulsed tin droplet plasma to produce a pattern by using a reflective photomask to expose a substrate covered by photoresist.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Tin ions in the ionic states from Sn IX to Sn XIV give photon emission spectral peaks around 13.5 nm from 4p64d*n* – 4p54d*n*+1 + 4d*n*−14f ionic state transitions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In the 1960s, visible light was used for the production of integrated circuits, with wavelengths as short as 435 nm (mercury G line).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Later, ultraviolet (UV) light was used, at first with a wavelength of 365 nm (mercury I line), then with excimer wavelengths, first of 248 nm (krypton fluoride laser), then 193 nm (argon fluoride laser), which was called deep UV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The next step, going even smaller, was called extreme UV, or EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV light is absorbed by glass and air, so instead of using lenses to focus the beams of light as done previously, mirrors in vacuum would be needed.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A reliable production of EUV was also problematic.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Then, leading producers of steppers Canon and Nikon stopped development.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] While working at Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in mid-1980s Japan, engineer Hiroo Kinoshita first proposed the concept of EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] He tested the idea and successfully demonstrated the first EUV images at a 1986 Japan Society of Applied Physics (JSAP) meeting.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Despite initial scepticism in Japan, Kinoshita continued EUV research at NTT and organized joint US-Japan research on EUV in the early 1990s.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In 1991, scientists at Bell Labs published a paper demonstrating the possibility of using a wavelength of 13.8 nm for the so-called soft X-ray projection lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] To address the challenge of EUV lithography, researchers at Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, and Sandia National Laboratories were funded in the 1990s to perform basic research into the technical obstacles.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The results of this successful effort were disseminated via a public/private partnership Cooperative R&D Agreement (CRADA).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The CRADA consisted of a consortium of private companies and the Labs, manifested as an entity called the Extreme Ultraviolet Limited Liability Company (EUV LLC).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Meanwhile, back in Japan, EUV technology development was pursued in the 1990s through the ASET (Association of Super-Advanced Electronics Technologies) and Extreme Ultraviolet Lithography Development Association (EUVA) programs.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Intel, Canon, and Nikon (leaders in the field at the time), as well as the Dutch company ASML and Silicon Valley Group (SVG) all sought licensing.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In 2001, SVG was acquired by ASML, helping ASML become the leading benefactor of the critical technology.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This led MIT Technology Review to name it "the machine that saved Moore's law".
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Their first prototype in 2006 produced one wafer in 23 hours.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] As of 2022, a scanner produces up to 200 wafers per hour.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The scanner uses Zeiss optics, which that company calls "the most precise mirrors in the world", produced by locating imperfections and then knocking off individual molecules with techniques such as ion beam figuring.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This made the once small company ASML the world leader in the production of scanners and monopolist in this cutting-edge technology and resulted in a record turnover of 27.4 billion euros in 2021, dwarfing their competitors Canon and Nikon, who were denied IP access.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Because it is such a key technology for development in many fields, the United States licenser pressured Dutch authorities to not sell these machines to China.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] ASML has followed the guidelines of Dutch export controls and until further notice will have no authority to ship the machines to China.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] China, at the same time, also has invested heavily into their domestic EUV project, and Chinese leading companies such as Huawei and SMEE also filed patents for their alternative proposals relevant to EUV technologies.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In December 2025, Reuters reported that China had secretly completed a prototype EUV machine in Shenzhen, which was expected to produce working chips between 2028 and 2030.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Along with multiple patterning, EUV has paved the way for higher transistor densities, allowing the production of higher-performance processors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Smaller transistors also require less power to operate, resulting in more energy-efficient electronics.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Requirements for EUV steppers, given the number of layers in the design that require EUV, the number of machines, and the desired throughput of the fab, assuming 24 hours per day operation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV photomasks work by reflecting light, which is achieved by using multiple alternating layers of molybdenum and silicon.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is in contrast to conventional photomasks which work by blocking light using a single chromium layer on a quartz substrate.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The multilayer may be protected by a thin ruthenium layer, called a capping layer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The pattern is defined in a tantalum-based absorbing layer over the capping layer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Blank photomasks are mainly made by two companies: AGC Inc. and Hoya Corporation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Ion-beam deposition equipment mainly made by Veeco is often used to deposit the multilayer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A blank photomask is covered with photoresist, which is then baked (solidified) in an oven, and later the pattern is defined on the photoresist using maskless lithography with an electron beam.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The exposed photoresist is developed (removed), and the unprotected areas are etched.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The remaining photoresist is then removed.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Masks are then inspected and later repaired using an electron beam.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Etching must be done only in the absorbing layer and thus there is a need to distinguish between the capping and the absorbing layer, which is known as etch selectivity and is unlike etching in conventional photomasks, which only have one layer critical to their function.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] An EUV tool (EUV photolithography machine) has a laser-driven tin plasma light source, reflective optics comprising multilayer mirrors, contained within a hydrogen gas ambient.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The hydrogen is used to keep the EUV collector mirror, as the first mirror collecting EUV emitted over a large range in angle (~2π sr) from the tin plasma, in the source free of tin deposition.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUVL is a significant departure from the deep-ultraviolet lithography standard.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUVL systems, as of 2002–2009, contain at least two condenser multilayer mirrors, six projection multilayer mirrors and a multilayer object (mask).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Since the mirrors absorb 96% of the EUV light, the ideal EUV source needs to be much brighter than its predecessors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV source development has focused on plasmas generated by laser or discharge pulses.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The mirror responsible for collecting the light is directly exposed to the plasma and is vulnerable to damage from high-energy ions and other debris such as tin droplets, which require the costly collector mirror to be replaced every year.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The required utility resources are significantly larger for EUV compared to 193 nm immersion, even with two exposures using the latter.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Additionally, to confine ion debris, a superconducting magnet may be required.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A typical EUV tool weighs nearly 200 tons and costs around US$180 million.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV tools consume at least 10× more energy than immersion tools.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The different degrees of resolution among the 0.33 NA tools are due to the different illumination options.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Despite the potential of the optics to reach sub-20 nm resolution, secondary electrons in resist practically limit the resolution to around 20 nm (more on this below).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Neutral atoms or condensed matter cannot emit EUV radiation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Ionization must precede EUV emission in matter.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The thermal production of multicharged positive ions is only possible in a hot dense plasma, which itself strongly absorbs EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] As of 2025, the established EUV light source is a laser-pulsed tin plasma.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The ions absorb the EUV light they emit and are easily neutralized by electrons in the plasma to lower charge states, which produce light mainly at other, unusable wavelengths, resulting in a much reduced efficiency of light generation for lithography at higher plasma power density.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The throughput is tied to the source power, divided by the dose.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A higher dose requires a slower stage motion (lower throughput) if pulse power cannot be increased.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV collector reflectivity degrades ~0.1–0.3% per billion 50 kHz pulses (~10% in ~2 weeks), leading to loss of uptime and throughput, while even for the first few billion pulses (within one day), there is still 20% (±10%) fluctuation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This could be due to the accumulating tin residue mentioned above which is not completely cleaned off.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] On the other hand, conventional immersion lithography tools for double-patterning provide consistent output for up to a year.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Recently, the NXE:3400B illuminator features a smaller pupil fill ratio (PFR) down to 20% without transmission loss.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] PFR is maximized and greater than 0.2 around a metal pitch of 45 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Due to the use of EUV mirrors which also absorb EUV light, only a small fraction of the source light is finally available at the wafer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] There are 4 mirrors used for the illumination optics and 6 mirrors for the projection optics.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The EUV mask or reticle is itself an additional mirror.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] With 11 reflections, only ~2% of the EUV source light is available at the wafer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The throughput is determined by the EUV resist dose, which in turn depends on the required resolution.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A dose of 40 mJ/cm2 is expected to be maintained for adequate throughput.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The EUV light source limits tool uptime besides throughput.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In a two-week period, for example, over seven hours downtime may be scheduled, while total actual downtime including unscheduled issues could easily exceed a day.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A dose error over 2% warrants tool downtime.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The wafer exposure throughput steadily expanded up to around 1000 wafers per day (per system) over the 2019–2022 period, indicating substantial idle time, while at the same time running >120 wafers per day on a number of multipatterned EUV layers, for an EUV wafer on average.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV (10–121 nm) is the band longer than X-rays (0.1–10 nm) and shorter than the hydrogen Lyman-alpha line (121 nm).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] While state-of-the-art 193 nm ArF excimer lasers offer intensities of 200 W/cm2, lasers for producing EUV-generating plasmas need to be much more intense, on the order of 1011 W/cm2.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A state-of-the-art ArF immersion lithography 120 W light source requires no more than 40 kW electrical power, while EUV sources are targeted to exceed 40 kW.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The optical power target for EUV lithography is at least 250 W, while for other conventional lithography sources, it is much less.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For example, immersion lithography light sources target 90 W, dry ArF sources 45 W, and KrF sources 40 W.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] High-NA EUV sources are expected to require at least 500 W.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A fundamental aspect of EUVL tools, resulting from the use of reflective optics, is the off-axis illumination (at an angle of 6°, in different direction at different positions within the illumination slit) on a multilayer mask (reticle).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This leads to shadowing effects resulting in asymmetry in the diffraction pattern that degrade pattern fidelity in various ways as described below.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For example, one side (behind the shadow) would appear brighter than the other (within the shadow).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The behavior of light rays within the plane of reflection (affecting horizontal lines) is different from the behavior of light rays out of the plane of reflection (affecting vertical lines).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Most conspicuously, identically sized horizontal and vertical lines on the EUV mask are printed at different sizes on the wafer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The combination of the off-axis asymmetry and the mask shadowing effect leads to a fundamental inability of two identical features even in close proximity to be in focus simultaneously.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] One of EUVL's key issues is the asymmetry between the top and bottom line of a pair of horizontal lines (the so-called "two-bar").
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Some ways to partly compensate are the use of assist features as well as asymmetric illumination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] An extension of the two-bar case to a grating consisting of many horizontal lines shows similar sensitivity to defocus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] It is manifest in the critical dimension (CD) difference between the top and bottom edge lines of the set of 11 horizontal lines.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Polarization by reflection also leads to partial polarization of EUV light, which favors imaging of lines perpendicular to the plane of the reflections.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Ultimately, this results in different positions of best focus for different pitches and different illumination angles.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Generally, the image shift is balanced out due to illumination source points being paired (each on opposite sides of the optical axis).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, the separate images are superposed and the resulting image contrast is degraded when the individual source image shifts are large enough.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The phase difference ultimately also determines the best focus position.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The multilayer is also responsible for image shifting due to phase shifts from diffracted light within the multilayer itself.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is inevitable due to light passing twice through the mask pattern.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The use of reflection causes wafer exposure position to be extremely sensitive to the reticle flatness and the reticle clamp.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Reticle clamp cleanliness is therefore required to be maintained.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Small (milliradian-scale) deviations in mask flatness in the local slope, coupled with wafer defocus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] More significantly, mask defocus has been found to result in large overlay errors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In particular, for a 10 nm node metal 1 layer (including 48 nm, 64 nm, 70 nm pitches, isolated, and power lines), the uncorrectable pattern placement error was 1 nm for 40 nm mask z-position shift.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is a global pattern shift of the layer with respect to previously defined layers.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, features at different locations will also shift differently due to different local deviations from mask flatness, e.g., from defects buried under the multilayer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] It can be estimated that the contribution of mask non-flatness to overlay error is roughly 1/40 times the peak-to-valley thickness variation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] With the blank peak-to-valley spec of 50 nm, ~1.25 nm image placement error is possible.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Blank thickness variations up to 80 nm also contribute, which lead to up to 2 nm image shift.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The off-axis illumination of the reticle is also the cause of non-telecentricity in wafer defocus, which consumes most of the 1.4 nm overlay budget of the NXE:3400 EUV scanner even for design rules as loose as 100 nm pitch.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Wafer defocus also leads to image placement errors due to deviations from local mask flatness.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] If the local slope is indicated by an angle α, the image is projected to be shifted in a 4× projection tool by 8α × (DOF/2) = 4α DOF, where DOF is the depth of focus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For a depth of focus of 100 nm, a small local deviation from flatness of 2.5 mrad (0.14°) can lead to a pattern shift of 1 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Simulations as well as experiments have shown that pupil imbalances in EUV lithography can result in pitch-dependent pattern placement errors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Since the pupil imbalance changes with EUV collector mirror aging or contamination, such placement errors may not be stable over time.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The situation is specifically challenging for logic devices, where multiple pitches have critical requirements at the same time.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The issue is ideally addressed by multiple exposures with tailored illuminations.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The direction of illumination is also highly dependent on slit position, essentially rotated azimuthally.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Nanya Technology and Synopsys found that horizontal vs. vertical bias changed across slit with dipole illumination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The rotating plane of incidence (azimuthal range within −25° to 25°) is confirmed in the SHARP actinic review microscope at CXRO which mimics the optics for EUV projection lithography systems.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The reason for this is that a mirror is used to transform straight rectangular fields into arc-shaped fields.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In order to preserve a fixed plane of incidence, the reflection from the previous mirror would be from a different angle with the surface for a different slit position; this causes non-uniformity of reflectivity.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] To preserve uniformity, rotational symmetry with a rotating plane of incidence is used.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] More generally, so-called "ring-field" systems reduce aberrations by relying on the rotational symmetry of an arc-shaped field derived from an off-axis annulus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is preferred, as reflective systems must use off-axis paths, which aggravate aberrations.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hence identical die patterns within different halves of the arc-shaped slit would require different OPC.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This renders them uninspectable by die-to-die comparison, as they are no longer truly identical dies.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For pitches requiring dipole, quadrupole, or hexapole illumination, the rotation also causes mismatch with the same pattern layout at a different slit position, i.e., edge vs. center.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Even with annular or circular illumination, the rotational symmetry is destroyed by the angle-dependent multilayer reflectance described above.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Although the azimuthal angle range is about ±20° (field data indicated over 18°) on 0.33 NA scanners, at 7 nm design rules (36–40 nm pitch), the tolerance for illumination can be ±15°, or even less.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Annular illumination nonuniformity and asymmetry also significantly impact the imaging.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Newer systems have azimuthal angle ranges going up to ±30°.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] On 0.33 NA systems, 30 nm pitch and lower already suffer sufficient reduction of pupil fill to significantly affect throughput.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The larger incident angle for pitch-dependent dipole illumination trend across slit does not affect horizontal line shadowing so much, but vertical line shadowing does increase going from center to edge.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In addition, higher-NA systems may offer limited relief from shadowing, as they target tight pitches.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The slit position dependence is particularly difficult for the tilted patterns encountered in DRAM.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Besides the more complicated effects due to shadowing and pupil rotation, tilted edges are converted to stair shape, which may be distorted by OPC.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In fact, the 32 nm pitch DRAM by EUV will lengthen up to at least 9*F*2 cell area, where *F* is the active area half-pitch (traditionally, it had been 6*F*2).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] With a 2-D self-aligned double-patterning active area cut, the cell area is still lower at 8.9*F*2.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The thermally induced aberrations are expected to exhibit differences among different positions across the slit, corresponding to different field positions, as each position encounters different parts of the deformed mirrors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Ironically, the use of substrate materials with high thermal and mechanical stability make it more difficult to compensate wavefront errors.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In combination with the range of wavelengths, the rotated plane of incidence aggravates the already severe stochastic impact on EUV imaging.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Unlike deep ultraviolet (DUV) lithography sources, based on excimer lasers, EUV plasma sources produce light across a broad range of wavelengths roughly spanning a 2% FWHM bandwidth near 13.5 nm (13.36 – 13.65 nm at 50% power).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV (10–121 nm) is the band longer than X-Rays (0.1–10 nm) and shorter than the hydrogen Lyman-alpha line.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Though the EUV spectrum is not completely monochromatic, nor even as spectrally pure as DUV laser sources, the working wavelength has generally been taken to be 13.5 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In actuality, the reflected power is distributed mostly in the 13.3-13.7 nm range.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The bandwidth of EUV light reflected by a multilayer mirror used for EUV lithography is over +/-2% (>270 pm); the phase changes due to wavelength changes at a given illumination angle may be calculated and compared to the aberration budget.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Wavelength dependence of reflectance also affects the apodization, or illumination distribution across the pupil (for different angles); different wavelengths effectively 'see' different illuminations as they are reflected differently by the multilayer of the mask.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This effective source illumination tilt can lead to large image shifts due to defocus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Conversely, the peak reflected wavelength varies across the pupil due to different incident angles.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is aggravated when the angles span a wide radius, e.g., annular illumination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The peak reflectance wavelength increases for smaller incident angles.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Aperiodic multilayers have been proposed to reduce the sensitivity at the cost of lower reflectivity but are too sensitive to random fluctuations of layer thicknesses, such as from thickness control imprecision or interdiffusion.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A narrower bandwidth would increase sensitivity to mask absorber and buffer thickness on the 1 nm scale.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Flare is the presence of background light originating from scattering off of surface features which are not resolved by the light.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In EUV systems, this light can be EUV or out-of-band (OoB) light that is also produced by the EUV source.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The OoB light adds the complication of affecting the resist exposure in ways other than accounted for by the EUV exposure.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] OoB light exposure may be alleviated by a layer coated above the resist, as well as 'black border' features on the EUV mask.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, the layer coating inevitably absorbs EUV light, and the black border adds EUV mask processing cost.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A key challenge for EUV is the counter-scaling behavior of the line tip-to-tip (T2T) distance as half-pitch (hp) is scaled down.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This is in part due to lower image contrast for the binary masks used in EUV lithography, which is not encountered with the use of phase shift masks in immersion lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The rounding of the corners of the line end leads to line end shortening, and this is worse for binary masks.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The use of phase-shift masks in EUV lithography has been studied but encounters difficulties from phase control in thin layers as well as the bandwidth of the EUV light itself.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] More conventionally, optical proximity correction (OPC) is used to address the corner rounding and line-end shortening.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In spite of this, it has been shown that the tip-to-tip resolution and the line tip printability are traded off against each other, being effectively CDs of opposite polarity.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In unidirectional metal layers, tip-to-tip spacing is one of the more severe issues for single exposure patterning.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For the 40 nm pitch vertical lines, an 18 nm nominal tip-to-tip drawn gap resulted in an actual tip-to-tip distance of 29 nm with OPC, while for 32 nm pitch horizontal lines, the tip-to-tip distance with a 14 nm nominal gap went to 31 nm with OPC.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] These actual tip-to-tip distances define a lower limit of the half-pitch of the metal running in the direction perpendicular to the tip.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In this case, the lower limit is around 30 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] With further optimization of the illumination (discussed in the section on source-mask optimization), the lower limit can be further reduced to around 25 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For larger pitches, where conventional illumination can be used, the line tip-to-tip distance is generally larger.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For the 24 nm half-pitch lines, with a 20 nm nominally drawn gap, the distance was actually 45 nm, while for 32 nm half-pitch lines, the same nominal gap resulted in a tip-to-tip distance of 34 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] With OPC, these become 39 nm and 28 nm for 24 nm half-pitch and 32 nm half-pitch, respectively.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Assist features are often used to help balance asymmetry from non-telecentricity at different slit positions, due to different illumination angles, starting at the 7 nm node, where the pitch is ~ 41 nm for a wavelength ~13.5 nm and NA=0.33, corresponding to k1 ~ 0.5.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, the asymmetry is reduced but not eliminated, since the assist features mainly enhance the highest spatial frequencies, whereas intermediate spatial frequencies, which also affect feature focus and position, are not much affected.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The coupling between the primary image and the self images is too strong for the asymmetry to be eliminated by assist features; only asymmetric illumination can achieve this.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Assist features may also get in the way of access to power/ground rails.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Power rails are expected to be wider, which also limits the effectiveness of using assist features, by constraining the local pitch.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Local pitches between 1× and 2× the minimum pitch forbid assist feature placement, as there is simply no room to preserve the local pitch symmetry.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In fact, for the application to the two-bar asymmetry case, the optimum assist feature placement may be less than or exceed the two-bar pitch.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Depending on the parameter to be optimized (process window area, depth of focus, exposure latitude), the optimum assist feature configuration can be very different, e.g., pitch between assist feature and bar being different from two-bar pitch, symmetric or asymmetric, etc..
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At pitches smaller than 58 nm, there is a tradeoff between depth of focus enhancement and contrast loss by assist feature placement.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Generally, there is still a focus-exposure tradeoff as the dose window is constrained by the need to have the assist features not print accidentally.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] An additional concern comes from shot noise; sub-resolution assist features (SRAFs) cause the required dose to be lower, so as not to print the assist features accidentally.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This results in fewer photons defining smaller features (see discussion in section on shot noise).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] As SRAFs are smaller features than primary features and are not supposed to receive doses high enough to print, they are more susceptible to stochastic dose variations causing printing errors; this is particularly prohibitive for EUV, where phase-shift masks may need to be used.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Due to the effects of non-telecentricity, standard illumination pupil shapes, such as disc or annular, are not sufficient to be used for feature sizes of ~20 nm or below (10 nm node and beyond).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Instead certain parts of the pupil (often over 50%) must be asymmetrically excluded.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The parts to be excluded depend on the pattern.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In particular, the densest allowed lines need to be aligned along one direction and prefer a dipole shape.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For this situation, double exposure lithography would be required for 2D patterns, due to the presence of both X- and Y-oriented patterns, each requiring its own 1D pattern mask and dipole orientation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] There may be 200–400 illuminating points, each contributing its weight of the dose to balance the overall image through focus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Thus the shot noise effect (to be discussed later) critically affects the image position through focus, in a large population of features.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Double- or multiple-patterning would also be required if a pattern consists of sub-patterns which require significantly different optimized illuminations, due to different pitches, orientations, shapes, and sizes.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Largely due to the slit shape, and the presence of residual aberrations, the effectiveness of SMO varies across slit position.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At each slit position, there are different aberrations and different azimuthal angles of incidence leading to different shadowing.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Consequently, there could be uncorrected variations across slit for aberration-sensitive features, which may not be obviously seen with regular line-space patterns.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At each slit position, although optical proximity correction (OPC), including the assist features mentioned above, may also be applied to address the aberrations, they also feedback into the illumination specification, since the benefits differ for different illumination conditions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This would necessitate the use of different source-mask combinations at each slit position, i.e., multiple mask exposures per layer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The above-mentioned chromatic aberrations, due to mask-induced apodization, also lead to inconsistent source-mask optimizations for different wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The best focus for a given feature size varies as a strong function of pitch, polarity, and orientation under a given illumination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At 36 nm pitch, horizontal and vertical darkfield features have more than 30 nm difference of focus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The 34 nm pitch and 48 nm pitch features have the largest difference of best focus regardless of feature type.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In the 48–64 nm pitch range, the best focus position shifts roughly linearly as a function of pitch, by as much as 10–20 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For the 34–48 nm pitch range, the best focus position shifts roughly linearly in the opposite direction as a function of pitch.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This can be correlated with the phase difference between the zero and first diffraction orders.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Assist features, if they can fit within the pitch, were found not to reduce this tendency much, for a range of intermediate pitches, or even worsened it for the case of 18–27 nm and quasar illumination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] 50 nm contact holes on 100 nm and 150 pitches had best focus positions separated by roughly 25 nm; smaller features are expected to be worse.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Contact holes in the 48–100 nm pitch range showed a 37 nm best focus range.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The best focus position vs. pitch is also dependent on resist.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Critical layers often contain lines at one minimum pitch of one polarity, e.g., darkfield trenches, in one orientation, e.g., vertical, mixed with spaces of the other polarity of the other orientation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This often magnifies the best focus differences, and challenges the tip-to-tip and tip-to-line imaging.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A consequence of SMO and shifting focus windows has been the reduction of pupil fill.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In other words, the optimum illumination is necessarily an optimized overlap of the preferred illuminations for the various patterns that need to be considered.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This leads to lower pupil fill providing better results.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, throughput is affected below 20% pupil fill due to absorption.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A commonly touted advantage of EUV has been the relative ease of lithography, as indicated by the ratio of feature size to the wavelength multiplied by the numerical aperture, also known as the k1 ratio.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] An 18 nm metal linewidth has a k1 of 0.44 for 13.5 nm wavelength, 0.33 NA, for example.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For the k1 approaching 0.5, some weak resolution enhancement including attenuated phase shift masks has been used as essential to production with the ArF laser wavelength (193 nm), whereas this resolution enhancement is not available for EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In particular, 3D mask effects including scattering at the absorber edges distort the desired phase profile.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Also, the phase profile is effectively derived from the plane wave spectrum reflected from the multilayer through the absorber rather than the incident plane wave.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Without absorbers, near-field distortion also occurs at an etched multilayer sidewall due to the oblique incidence illumination; some light traverses only a limited number of bilayers near the sidewall.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Additionally, the different polarizations (TE and TM) have different phase shifts.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Fundamentally, a chromeless phase shift mask enables pitch splitting by suppression of the zeroth diffracted order on the mask, but fabricating a high quality phase shift mask for EUV is certainly not a trivial task.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] One possible way to achieve this is through spatial filtering at the Fourier plane of the mask pattern.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At Lawrence Berkeley National Lab, the light of the zeroth order is a centrally obscured system, and the +/-1 diffracted orders will be captured by the clear aperture, providing a functional equivalent to the chromeless phase shift mask while using a conventional binary amplitude mask.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV light generates photoelectrons upon absorption by matter.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] These photoelectrons in turn generate secondary electrons, which slow down before engaging in chemical reactions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At sufficient doses 40 eV electrons are known to penetrate 180 nm thick resist leading to development.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] At a dose of 160 μC/cm2, corresponding to 15 mJ/cm2 EUV dose assuming one electron/photon, 30 eV electrons removed 7 nm of PMMA resist after standard development.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For a higher 30 eV dose of 380 μC/cm2, equivalent to 36 mJ/cm2 at one electron/photon, 10.4 nm of PMMA resist are removed.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] These indicate the distances the electrons can travel in resist, regardless of direction.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The degree of photoelectron emission from the layer underlying the EUV photoresist has been shown to affect the depth of focus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Unfortunately, hardmask layers tend to increase photoelectron emission, degrading the depth of focus.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Electrons from defocused images in the resist can also affect the best focus image.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The randomness of the number of secondary electrons is itself a source of stochastic behavior in EUV resist images.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The scale length of electron blur itself has a distribution.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Intel demonstrated with a rigorous simulation that EUV-released electrons scatter distances larger than 15 nm in EUV resists.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The electron blur is also affected by total internal reflection from the top surface of the resist film.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] A more realistic description of the electron blur uses the difference of two exponential functions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In chemically amplified resists, acid blur can help to smoothen edge roughness, but low spatial-frequency roughness still remains, whereas in metal oxide resists, even high spatial-frequency roughness remains, since there is no acid blur smoothing.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] More blur can smooth the smaller scale roughness, but at the cost of reduced image contrast.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Secondary electrons from layers underneath the resist can affect the resist profile as well as pattern collapse.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hence, selection of such both the underlayer and the layer under that layer are important considerations for EUV lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Moreover, the electrons from defocused images can aggravate the stochastic nature of the image.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Due to the high efficiency of absorption of EUV by photoresists, heating and outgassing become primary concerns.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] One well-known issue is contamination deposition on the resist from ambient or outgassed hydrocarbons, which results from EUV- or electron-driven reactions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Organic photoresists outgas hydrocarbons while metal oxide photoresists outgas water and oxygen and metal (in a hydrogen ambient); the last is uncleanable.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The carbon contamination is known to affect multilayer reflectivity while the oxygen is particularly harmful for the ruthenium capping layers (relatively stable under EUV and hydrogen conditions) on the EUV multilayer optics.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV resist degradation increases with dose, as evidenced by outgassing of key components.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Several studies have shown that EUV resists are thinned as dose increases.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] For metal oxide resists, IMEC had shown that counterion loss was significant during EUV exposure.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Atomic hydrogen in the tool chambers is used to clean tin and carbon which deposit on the EUV optical surfaces.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Redeposition may also occur by other intermediate reactions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The redeposited Sn might be subsequently removed by atomic-hydrogen exposure.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] However, overall, the tin cleaning efficiency (the ratio of the removed tin flux from a tin sample to the atomic-hydrogen flux to the tin sample) is less than 0.01%, due to both redeposition and hydrogen desorption, leading to formation of hydrogen molecules at the expense of atomic hydrogen.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The tin cleaning efficiency for tin oxide is found roughly twice higher than that of tin (with a native oxide layer of ~2 nm on it).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Injecting a small amount of oxygen to the light source may improve the tin cleaning rate.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Removal of tin particles is crucial for maintaining mask performance, as tin is used to generate EUV light and continuously contaminates EUV masks during lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hydrogen also reacts with metal-containing compounds to reduce them to metal, and diffuses through the silicon and molybdenum in the multilayer, eventually causing blistering.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Capping layers that mitigate hydrogen-related damage often reduce reflectivity to well below 70%.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Capping layers are known to be permeable to ambient gases including oxygen and hydrogen, as well as susceptible to the hydrogen-induced blistering defects.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hydrogen may also react with the capping layer, resulting in its removal.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] TSMC proposed some means for mitigating hydrogen blistering defects on EUV masks, which may impact productivity.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hydrogen can penetrate molten tin, creating hydrogen bubbles inside it.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] If the bubbles move at the molten tin surface, then it bursts with tin, resulting in tin spreading over a large angle range.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] This phenomenon is called tin spitting and is one of EUV Collector contamination sources.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Hydrogen also reacts with resists to etch or decompose them.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Besides photoresist, hydrogen plasmas can also etch silicon, albeit very slowly.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] To help mitigate the above effects, the latest EUV tool introduced in 2017, the NXE:3400B, features a membrane that separates the wafer from the projection optics of the tool, protecting the latter from outgassing from the resist on the wafer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The membrane contains layers which absorb DUV and IR radiation, and transmits 85–90% of the incident EUV radiation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] There is of course, accumulated contamination from wafer outgassing as well as particles in general (although the latter are out of focus, they may still obstruct light).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] EUV lithographic systems using EUV light operate in 1–10 Pa hydrogen background gas.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The plasma is a source of VUV radiation as well as electrons and hydrogen ions This plasma is known to etch exposed materials.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] In 2023, a study supported at TSMC was published which indicated net charging by electrons from the plasma as well as from electron emission.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] The charging was found to occur even outside the EUV exposure area, indicating that the surrounding area had been exposed to electrons.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p01] Due to chemical sputtering of carbon by the hydrogen plasma, there can be generation of nanoparticles, which can obstruct the EUV resist exposure.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Reducing defects on extreme ultraviolet (EUV) masks is currently one of the most critical issues to be addressed for commercialization of EUV lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Defects can be buried underneath or within the multilayer stack or be on top of the multilayer stack.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Mesas or protrusions form on the sputtering targets used for multilayer deposition, which may fall off as particles during the multilayer deposition.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In fact, defects of atomic scale height (0.3–0.5 nm) with 100 nm FWHM can still be printable by exhibiting 10% CD impact.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] IBM and Toppan reported at Photomask Japan 2015 that smaller defects, e.g., 50 nm size, can have 10% CD impact even with 0.6 nm height, yet remain undetectable.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Furthermore, the edge of a phase defect will further reduce reflectivity by more than 10% if its deviation from flatness exceeds 3 degrees, due to the deviation from the target angle of incidence of 84 degrees with respect to the surface.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Even if the defect height is shallow, the edge still deforms the overlying multilayer, producing an extended region where the multilayer is sloped.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The more abrupt the deformation, the narrower the defect edge extension, the greater the loss in reflectivity.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] EUV mask defect repair is also more complicated due to the across-slit illumination variation mentioned above.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Due to the varying shadowing sensitivity across the slit, the repair deposition height must be controlled very carefully, being different at different positions across the EUV mask illumination slit.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] GlobalFoundries and Lawrence Berkeley Labs carried out a Monte Carlo study to simulate the effects of intermixing between the molybdenum (Mo) and silicon (Si) layers in the multilayer that is used to reflect EUV light from the EUV mask.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The results indicated high sensitivity to the atomic-scale variations of layer thickness.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Such variations could not be detected by wide-area reflectivity measurements but would be significant on the scale of the critical dimension (CD).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The local variation of reflectivity could be on the order of 10% for a few nm standard deviation.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Multiple EUV pulses at less than 10 mJ/cm2 could accumulate damage to a Ru-capped Mo/Si multilayer mirror optic element.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The angle of incidence was 16° or 0.28 rads, which is within the range of angles for a 0.33 NA optical system.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Production EUV tools need a pellicle to protect the mask from contamination.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Pellicles are normally expected to protect the mask from particles during transport, entry into or exit from the exposure chamber, as well as the exposure itself.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Without pellicles, particle adders would reduce yield, which has not been an issue for conventional optical lithography with 193 nm light and pellicles.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, for EUV, the feasibility of pellicle use is severely challenged, due to the required thinness of the shielding films to prevent excessive EUV absorption.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Particle contamination would be prohibitive if pellicles were not stable above 200 W, i.e., the targeted power for manufacturing.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Heating of the EUV mask pellicle (film temperature up to 750 K for 80 W incident power) is a significant concern, due to the resulting deformation and transmission decrease.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] ASML developed a 70 nm thick polysilicon pellicle membrane, which allows EUV transmission of 82%; however, less than half of the membranes survived expected EUV power levels.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] SiNx pellicle membranes also failed at 82 W equivalent EUV source power levels.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] At target 250 W levels, the pellicle is expected to reach 686 degrees Celsius, well over the melting point of aluminum.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Alternative materials need to allow sufficient transmission as well as maintain mechanical and thermal stability.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, graphite, graphene or other carbon nanomaterials (nanosheets, nanotubes) are damaged by EUV due to the release of electrons and also too easily etched in the hydrogen cleaning plasma expected to be deployed in EUV scanners.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Hydrogen plasmas can also etch silicon as well.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A coating helps improve hydrogen resistance, but this reduces transmission and/or emissivity, and may also affect mechanical stability (e.g., bulging).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Wrinkles on pellicles can cause CD nonuniformity due to uneven absorption; this is worse for smaller wrinkles and more coherent illumination, i.e., lower pupil fill.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In the absence of pellicles, EUV mask cleanliness would have to be checked before actual product wafers are exposed, using wafers specially prepared for defect inspection.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] These wafers are inspected after printing for repeating defects indicating a dirty mask; if any are found, the mask must be cleaned and another set of inspection wafers are exposed, repeating the flow until the mask is clean.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Any affected product wafers must be reworked.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] TSMC reported starting limited use of its own pellicle in 2019 and continuing to expand afterwards, and Samsung is planning pellicle introduction in 2022.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, follow-up reporting indicating no users of EUV pellicles due to accelerated damage under higher power.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Without pellicles, yield can be significantly reduced by particles added onto the die exposure area of the mask.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The particle size also determines if it can be fatal to yield.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] As discussed above, with regard to contamination removal, hydrogen used in recent EUV systems can penetrate into the EUV mask layers.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] TSMC indicated in its patent that hydrogen would enter from the mask edge.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Once trapped, bulge defects or blisters were produced, which could lead to film peeling.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] These are essentially the blister defects which arise after a sufficient number of EUV mask exposures in the hydrogen environment.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] EUV lithography is particularly sensitive to stochastic effects.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In a large population of features printed by EUV, although the overwhelming majority are resolved, some suffer complete failure to print, e.g. missing holes or bridging lines.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A known significant contribution to this effect is the dose used to print.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] This is related to shot noise, to be discussed further below.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Due to the stochastic variations in arriving photon numbers, some areas designated to print actually fail to reach the threshold to print, leaving unexposed defect regions.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Some areas may be overexposed, leading to excessive resist loss or crosslinking.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The probability of stochastic failure increases exponentially as feature size decreases, and for the same feature size, increasing distance between features also significantly increases the probability.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Line cuts which are misshapen are a significant issue due to potential arcing and shorting.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Yield requires detection of stochastic failures down to below 1e-12.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The tendency to stochastic defects is worse from defocus over a large pupil fill.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Multiple failure modes may exist for the same population.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For example, besides bridging of trenches, the lines separating the trenches may be broken.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] This can be attributed to stochastic resist loss, from secondary electrons.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The coexistence of stochastically underexposed and overexposed defect regions leads to a loss of dose window at a certain post-etch defect level between the low-dose and high-dose patterning cliffs.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Hence, the resolution benefit from shorter wavelength is lost.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The resist underlayer also plays an important role.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] This could be due to the secondary electrons generated by the underlayer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Secondary electrons may remove over 10 nm of resist from the exposed edge.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Photon shot noise also leads to stochastic edge placement error.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The photon shot noise can be compensated to some degree by blurring factors such as secondary electrons or acids in chemically amplified resists; when significant the blur also reduces the image contrast at the edge.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] An edge placement error (EPE) as large as 8.8 nm was measured for a 48 nm pitch EUV-printed metal pattern.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] With the natural Poisson distribution due to the random arrival and absorption times of the photons, there is an expected natural dose (photon number) variation of at least several percent 3 sigma, making the exposure process susceptible to stochastic variations.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The dose variation leads to a variation of the feature edge position, effectively becoming a blur component.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Unlike the hard resolution limit imposed by diffraction, shot noise imposes a softer limit, with the main guideline being the ITRS line width roughness (LWR) spec of 8% (3s) of linewidth.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Increasing the dose will reduce the shot noise, but this also requires higher source power.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Aside from the resolution impact, higher dose also increases outgassing and limits throughput, and crosslinking occurs at very high dose levels.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For chemically amplified resists, higher dose exposure also increases line edge roughness due to acid generator decomposition.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Also, an upper limit to how much dose can be increased is imposed by resist loss.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Due to resist thinning with increased dose, EUV stochastic defectivity limits will define a narrow CD or dose window.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The thinner resist at higher incident dose reduces absorption, and hence, absorbed dose.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The thinner resist is also more susceptible to nanovoids leading to resist breaks.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Even with higher absorption at the same dose, EUV has a larger shot noise concern than the ArF (193 nm) wavelength, mainly because it is applied to thinner resists.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] There is also an extra component noise from the secondary electron emission.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Due to stochastic considerations, the IRDS 2022 lithography roadmap now acknowledges increasing doses for smaller feature sizes.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] EUV resolution will likely be compromised by stochastic effects.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Stochastic defect densities have exceeded 1/cm2, at 36 nm pitch; this is aggravated by electron blur.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In 2024, an EUV resist exposure by ASML revealed a missing+bridging 32 nm pitch contact hole defect density floor >0.25/cm2 (177 defects per wafer), made worse with thinner resist.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] ASML indicated 30 nm pitch would not use direct exposure but double patterning.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Besides lower absorbed photon density, the impact of stochastic effects on EUV resolution is also tied to the smaller molecular size of EUV resists.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] DRAM scaling will also become difficult at 10-11 nm design rules, due to EUV stochastics.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The storage node patterns, which are arranged in a hexagonal array, are particularly sensitive due to their reliance on hexapole EUV illumination, which splits the image into three different sub-images, each with a third of the dose.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Larger features may unexpectedly suffer from stochastic fluctuations as well, due to local peaks and valleys in their aerial image.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] IMEC's yield model updated in 2024 indicated that increased EUV use for 5nm node and beyond resulted in reduced yield, due to higher stochastic defectivity at tighter pitches.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] As of 2025, stochastic defect probabilities were on the order of ppm, and could also vary over an order of magnitude, leading to erratic yields.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For pitches less than half-wavelength divided by numerical aperture, dipole illumination is necessary.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] This illumination fills at most a leaf-shaped area at the edge of the pupil.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, due to 3D effects in the EUV mask, smaller pitches require even smaller portions of this leaf shape.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Below 20% of the pupil, the throughput and dose stability begin to suffer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Higher numerical aperture allows a higher pupil fill to be used for the same pitch, but depth of focus is significantly reduced.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A larger pupil fill is more susceptible to stochastic fluctuations from point to point in the pupil.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] EUV is anticipated to use double-patterning at around 34 nm pitch with 0.33 NA.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] This resolution is equivalent to '1Y' for DRAM.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In 2020, ASML reported that 5 nm M0 layer (30 nm minimum pitch) required double-patterning.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In H2 2018, TSMC confirmed that its 5 nm EUV scheme still used multi-patterning, also indicating that mask count did not decrease from its 7 nm node, which used extensive DUV multi-patterning, to its 5 nm node, which used extensive EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] EDA vendors also indicated the continued use of multi-patterning flows.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] While Samsung introduced its own 7 nm process with EUV single-patterning, it encountered severe photon shot noise causing excessive line roughness, which required higher dose, resulting in lower throughput.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] TSMC's 5 nm node uses even tighter design rules.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Samsung indicated smaller dimensions would have more severe shot noise.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In Intel's complementary lithography scheme at 20 nm half-pitch, EUV would be used only in a second line-cutting exposure after a first 193 nm line-printing exposure.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Multiple exposures would also be expected where two or more patterns in the same layer, e.g., different pitches or widths, must use different optimized source pupil shapes.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For example, when considering a staggered bar array of 64 nm vertical pitch, changing the horizontal pitch from 64 nm to 90 nm changes the optimized illumination significantly.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Source-mask optimization that is based on line-space gratings and tip-to-tip gratings only does not entail improvements for all parts of a logic pattern, e.g., a dense trench with a gap on one side.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In 2020, ASML reported that for the 3 nm node, center-to-center contact/via spacings of 40 nm or less would require double- or triple-patterning for some contact/via arrangements.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For the 24–36 nm metal pitch, it was found that using EUV as a (second) cutting exposure had a significantly wider process window than as a complete single exposure for the metal layer.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, using a second exposure in the LELE approach for double patterning does not get around the vulnerability to stochastic defects.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Multiple exposures of the same mask are also expected for defect management without pellicles, limiting productivity similarly to multiple-patterning.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Self-aligned litho-etch-litho-etch (SALELE) is a hybrid SADP/LELE technique whose implementation has started in 7 nm.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Self-aligned litho-etch-litho-etch (SALELE) has become an accepted form of double-patterning to be used with EUV.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In order to avoid higher doses for alleviating stochastic effects (even for 36 nm vias) splitting the pattern, leading to double patterning or multipatterning, would lead to a better image quality.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In fact, this occurs at large enough design rules (i.e., 36 nm) that it overlaps with DUV double patterning.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A return to extended generations of single-patterning would be possible with higher numerical aperture (NA) tools.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] An NA of 0.45 could require retuning of a few percent.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Increasing demagnification could avoid this retuning, but the reduced field size severely affects large patterns (one die per 26 mm × 33 mm field) such as the many-core multi-billion transistor 14 nm Xeon chips. by requiring field stitching of two mask exposures.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In 2015, ASML disclosed details of its anamorphic next-generation EUV scanner, with an NA of 0.55.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] These machines cost around US$360 million.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] The demagnification is increased from 4× to 8× only in one direction (in the plane of incidence).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] However, the 0.55 NA has a much smaller depth of focus than immersion lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Also, an anamorphic 0.52 NA tool has been found to exhibit too much CD and placement variability for 5 nm node single exposure and multi-patterning cutting.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] High-NA EUV tools focus horizontal and vertical lines differently from low-NA systems, due to the different demagnification for horizontal lines.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] High-NA EUV tools also suffer from obscuration, which can cause errors in the imaging of certain patterns.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Intel completed assembly of its first commercial high-NA tool, TWINSCAN EXE:5000, in its D1X R&D fab in Oregon in April 2024, with a second machine installed in October 2024.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] In late 2025, Intel installed the new TWINSCAN EXE:5200B for its upcoming 14A node, with volume production expected in 2027.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] For sub-2nm nodes, high-NA EUV systems will be affected by a host of issues: throughput, new masks, polarization, thinner resists, and secondary electron blur and randomness.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Reduced depth of focus requires resist thickness less than 30 nm, which in turn increases stochastic effects, due to reduced photon absorption.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Electron blur is estimated to be at least ~2 nm, which is enough to thwart the benefit of High-NA EUV lithography.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] Beyond high-NA, ASML in 2024 announced plans for the development of a hyper-NA EUV tool with an NA beyond 0.55, such as an NA of 0.75 or 0.85.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] These machines could cost US$720 million each and are expected to be available in 2030.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A problem with Hyper-NA is polarization of the EUV light causing a reduction in image contrast.
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] A much shorter wavelength (~6.7 nm) would be beyond EUV, and is often referred to as BEUV (beyond extreme ultraviolet).
[src:photolithography/extreme-ultraviolet-lithography-p02] With current technology, BEUV wavelengths would have worse shot noise effects without ensuring sufficient dose.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Immersion lithography replaces the usual air gap between the final lens and the wafer surface with a liquid medium that has a refractive index greater than one.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The angular resolution is increased by a factor equal to the refractive index of the liquid.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Current immersion lithography tools use highly purified water for this liquid, achieving feature sizes below 45 nanometers.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The ability to resolve features in optical lithography is directly related to the numerical aperture of the imaging equipment, the numerical aperture being the sine of the maximum refraction angle multiplied by the refractive index of the medium through which the light travels.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The lenses in the highest resolution "dry" photolithography scanners focus light in a cone whose boundary is nearly parallel to the wafer surface.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] As it is impossible to increase resolution by further refraction, additional resolution is obtained by inserting an immersion medium with a higher index of refraction between the lens and the wafer.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The blurriness is reduced by a factor equal to the refractive index of the medium.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] For example, for water immersion using ultraviolet light at 193 nm wavelength, the index of refraction is 1.44.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The resolution enhancement from immersion lithography is about 30–40% depending on materials used.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] However, the depth of focus, or tolerance in wafer topography flatness, is improved compared to the corresponding "dry" tool at the same resolution.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The idea for immersion lithography was patented in 1984 by Takanashi et al.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] It was also proposed by Taiwanese engineer Burn J.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] In 2004, IBM's director of silicon technology, Ghavam Shahidi, announced that IBM planned to commercialize lithography based on light filtered through water.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Defect concerns, e.g., water left behind (watermarks) and loss of resist-water adhesion (air gap or bubbles), have led to considerations of using a topcoat layer directly on top of the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] This topcoat would serve as a barrier for chemical diffusion between the liquid medium and the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] In addition, the interface between the liquid and the topcoat would be optimized for watermark reduction.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] At the same time, defects from topcoat use should be avoided.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] As of 2005, Topcoats had been tuned for use as antireflection coatings, especially for hyper-NA (NA>1) cases.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] By 2008, defect counts on wafers printed by immersion lithography had reached zero level capability.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] As of 2000, Polarization effects due to high angles of interference in the photoresist were considered as features approach 40 nm.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Hence, illumination sources generally need to be azimuthally polarized to match the pole illumination for ideal line-space imaging.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] As of 1996, this was achieved through higher stage speeds, which in turn, as of 2013 were allowed by higher power ArF laser pulse sources.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Specifically, the throughput is directly proportional to stage speed V, which is related to dose D and rectangular slit width S and slit intensity Iss (which is directly related to pulse power) by V=Iss*S/D.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The slit height is the same as the field height.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The slit width S, in turn, is limited by the number of pulses to make the dose (n), divided by the frequency of the laser pulses (f), at the maximum scan speed Vmax by S=Vmax*n/f.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] At a fixed frequency f and pulse number n, the slit width will be proportional to the maximum stage speed.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Hence, throughput at a given dose is improved by increasing maximum stage speed as well as increasing pulse power.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] In 2015 ASML reported that their TWINSCAN NXT:1980Di immersion lithography platform archieved throughputs of up to 275 WPH, targeted for high volume manufacturing.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] The resolution limit for a 1.35 NA immersion tool operating at 193 nm wavelength is 36 nm.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] Going beyond this limit to sub-20nm nodes requires multiple patterning.
[src:photolithography/immersion-lithography] In 2016 Samsung announced successful tests of a 10nm SoC using triple patterning, slated for mass production in 2017.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The process begins with a photosensitive material, called a photoresist, being applied to the substrate.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A photomask that contains the desired pattern is then placed over the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Light is shone through the photomask, exposing the photoresist in certain areas.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The exposed areas undergo a chemical change, making them either soluble or insoluble in a developer solution.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] After development, the pattern is transferred onto the sample through etching, chemical vapor deposition, physical vapor deposition, plating, or ion implantation processes.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography processes can be classified according to the type of light used, including ultraviolet lithography, deep ultraviolet lithography, extreme ultraviolet lithography (EUVL), and X-ray lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The wavelength of light used determines the minimum feature size that can be formed in the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Ultraviolet (UV) light is typically used.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography is the most common method for the semiconductor fabrication of integrated circuits ("ICs" or "chips"), such as solid-state memories and microprocessors.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It can create extremely small patterns, down to a few nanometers in size.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It provides precise control of the shape and size of the objects it creates.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It can create patterns over an entire wafer in a single step, quickly and with relatively low cost.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In complex integrated circuits, a wafer may go through the photolithographic cycle as many as 50 times.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It is also an important technique for microfabrication in general, such as the fabrication of microelectromechanical systems.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] However, photolithography cannot be used to produce masks on surfaces that are not perfectly flat.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] And, like all chip manufacturing processes, it requires extremely clean operating conditions.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography is a subclass of microlithography, the general term for processes that generate patterned thin films.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Other technologies in this broader class include the use of steerable electron beams, or more rarely, nanoimprinting, interference, magnetic fields, or scanning probes.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] On a broader level, it may compete with directed self-assembly of micro- and nanostructures.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography shares some fundamental principles with photography in that the pattern in the photoresist is created by exposing it to light — either directly by projection through a lens, or by illuminating a mask placed directly over the substrate, as in contact printing.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The technique can also be seen as a high precision version of the method used to make printed circuit boards.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The name originated from a loose analogy with the traditional photographic method of producing plates for lithographic printing on paper; however, subsequent stages in the process have more in common with etching than with traditional lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Conventional photoresists typically consist of three components: resin, sensitizer, and solvent.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The root words *photo*, *litho*, and *graphy* all have Greek origins, with the meanings 'light', 'stone' and 'writing' respectively.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] As suggested by the name compounded from them, *photolithography* is a printing method (originally based on the use of limestone printing plates) in which light plays an essential role.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In the 1820s, Nicephore Niepce invented a photographic process that used Bitumen of Judea, a natural asphalt, as the first photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A thin coating of the bitumen on a sheet of metal, glass or stone became less soluble where it was exposed to light; the unexposed parts could then be rinsed away with a suitable solvent, baring the material beneath, which was then chemically etched in an acid bath to produce a printing plate.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The light-sensitivity of bitumen was very poor and very long exposures were required, but despite the later introduction of more sensitive alternatives, its low cost and superb resistance to strong acids prolonged its commercial life into the early 20th century.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 1940, Oskar Süß created a *positive* photoresist by using diazonaphthoquinone, which worked in the opposite manner: the coating was initially insoluble and was rendered soluble where it was exposed to light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 1954, Louis Plambeck Jr. developed the Dycryl polymeric letterpress plate, which made the platemaking process faster.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Development of photoresists used to be carried out in batches of wafers (batch processing) dipped into a bath of developer, but modern process offerings do development one wafer at a time (single wafer processing) to improve process control.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 1957 Jules Andrus patented a photolithographic process for semiconductor fabrication, while working at Bell Labs.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] At the same time Moe Abramson and Stanislaus Danko of the US Army Signal Corps developed a technique for printing circuits.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 1952, the U.S. military assigned Jay W.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Nall at the National Bureau of Standards (later the U.S.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Army Diamond Ordnance Fuze Laboratory, which eventually merged to form the now-present Army Research Laboratory) with the task of finding a way to reduce the size of electronic circuits in order to better fit the necessary circuitry in the limited space available inside a proximity fuze.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Inspired by the application of photoresist, a photosensitive liquid used to mark the boundaries of rivet holes in metal aircraft wings, Nall determined that a similar process can be used to protect the germanium in the transistors and even pattern the surface with light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] During development, Lathrop and Nall were successful in creating a 2D miniaturized hybrid integrated circuit with transistors using this technique.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography would later contribute to the development of the first semiconductor ICs as well as the first microchips.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A single iteration of photolithography combines several steps in sequence.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Modern cleanrooms use automated, robotic wafer track systems to coordinate the process.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The procedure described here omits some advanced treatments, such as thinning agents.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The photolithography process is carried out by the wafer track and stepper/scanner, and the wafer track system and the stepper/scanner are installed side by side.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Wafer track systems are also known as wafer coater/developer systems, which perform the same functions.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Wafer tracks are named after the "tracks" used to carry wafers inside the machine, but modern machines do not use tracks.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] If organic or inorganic contaminations are present on the wafer surface, they are usually removed by wet chemical treatment, e.g. the RCA clean procedure based on solutions containing hydrogen peroxide.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Other solutions made with trichloroethylene, acetone or methanol can also be used to clean.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The wafer is initially heated to a temperature sufficient to drive off any moisture that may be present on the wafer surface; 150 °C for ten minutes is sufficient.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Wafers that have been in storage must be chemically cleaned to remove contamination.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A liquid or gaseous "adhesion promoter", such as Bis(trimethylsilyl)amine ("hexamethyldisilazane", HMDS), is applied to promote adhesion of the photoresist to the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The surface layer of silicon dioxide on the wafer reacts with HMDS to form tri-methylated silicon-dioxide, a highly water repellent layer not unlike the layer of wax on a car's paint.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This water repellent layer prevents the aqueous developer from penetrating between the photoresist layer and the wafer's surface, thus preventing so-called lifting of small photoresist structures in the (developing) pattern.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In order to ensure the development of the image, it is best covered and placed over a hot plate and let it dry while stabilizing the temperature at 120 °C.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The wafer is covered with photoresist liquid by spin coating.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Thus, the top layer of resist is quickly ejected from the wafer's edge while the bottom layer still creeps slowly radially along the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In this way, any 'bump' or 'ridge' of resist is removed, leaving a very flat layer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] However, viscous films may result in large edge beads which are areas at the edges of the wafer or photomask with increased resist thickness whose planarization has physical limits.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Often, Edge bead removal (EBR) is carried out, usually with a nozzle, to remove this extra resist as it could otherwise cause particulate contamination.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Final thickness is also determined by the evaporation of liquid solvents from the resist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] For very small, dense features (< 125 or so nm), lower resist thicknesses (< 0.5 microns) are needed to overcome collapse effects at high aspect ratios; typical aspect ratios are < 4:1.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The photoresist-coated wafer is then prebaked to drive off excess photoresist solvent, typically at 90 to 100 °C for 30 to 60 seconds on a hotplate.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A BARC coating (Bottom Anti-Reflectant Coating) may be applied before the photoresist is applied, to avoid reflections from occurring under the photoresist and to improve the photoresist's performance at smaller semiconductor nodes such as 45 nm and below.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Top Anti-Reflectant Coatings (TARCs) also exist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] EUV lithography is unique in the sense it allows for the use of photoresists with metal oxides.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] After prebaking, the photoresist is exposed to a pattern of intense light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The exposure to light causes a chemical change that allows some of the photoresist to be removed by a special solution, called "developer" by analogy with photographic developer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Positive photoresist, the most common type, becomes soluble in the developer when exposed; with negative photoresist, unexposed regions are soluble in the developer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A post-exposure bake (PEB) is performed before developing, typically to help reduce standing wave phenomena caused by the destructive and constructive interference patterns of the incident light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In deep ultraviolet lithography, chemically amplified resist (CAR) chemistry is used.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The develop chemistry is delivered on a spinner, much like photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Developers originally often contained sodium hydroxide (NaOH).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Metal-ion-free developers such as tetramethylammonium hydroxide (TMAH) are now used.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The temperature of the developer might be tightly controlled using jacketed (dual walled) hoses to within 0.2 °C.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The nozzle that coats the wafer with developer may influence the amount of developer that is necessary.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The resulting wafer is then "hard-baked" if a non-chemically amplified resist was used, typically at 120 to 180 °C for 20 to 30 minutes.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The hard bake solidifies the remaining photoresist, to make a more durable protecting layer in future ion implantation, wet chemical etching, or plasma etching.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] From preparation until this step, the photolithography procedure has been carried out by two machines: the photolithography stepper or scanner, and the coater/developer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The two machines are usually installed side by side, and are "linked" together.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In etching, a liquid ("wet") or plasma ("dry") chemical agent removes the uppermost layer of the substrate in the areas that are not protected by photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In semiconductor fabrication, dry etching techniques are generally used, as they can be made anisotropic, in order to avoid significant undercutting of the photoresist pattern.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This is essential when the width of the features to be defined is similar to or less than the thickness of the material being etched (i.e. when the aspect ratio approaches unity).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Wet etch processes are generally isotropic in nature, which is often indispensable for microelectromechanical systems, where suspended structures must be "released" from the underlying layer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The development of low-defectivity anisotropic dry-etch process has enabled the ever-smaller features defined photolithographically in the resist to be transferred to the substrate material.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] After a photoresist is no longer needed, it must be removed from the substrate.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This usually requires a liquid "resist stripper", which chemically alters the resist so that it no longer adheres to the substrate.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Alternatively, the photoresist may be removed by a plasma containing oxygen, which oxidizes it.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This process is called plasma ashing and resembles dry etching.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The use of 1-Methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP) solvent for photoresist is another method used to remove an image.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] When the resist has been dissolved, the solvent can be removed by heating to 80 °C without leaving any residue.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Exposure systems typically produce an image on the wafer using a photomask.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The photomask blocks light in some areas and lets it pass in others.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] (Maskless lithography projects a precise beam directly onto the wafer without using a mask, but it is not widely used in commercial processes.) Exposure systems may be classified by the optics that transfer the image from the mask to the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography produces better thin film transistor structures than printed electronics, due to smoother printed layers, less wavy patterns, and more accurate drain-source electrode registration.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A contact aligner, the simplest exposure system, puts a photomask in direct contact with the wafer and exposes it to a uniform light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A proximity aligner puts a small gap of around 5 microns between the photomask and wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In both cases, the mask covers the entire wafer, and simultaneously patterns every die.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Contact printing/lithography is liable to damage both the mask and the wafer, and this was the primary reason it was abandoned for high volume production.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Both contact and proximity lithography require the light intensity to be uniform across an entire wafer, and the mask to align precisely to features already on the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] As modern processes use increasingly large wafers, these conditions become increasingly difficult.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Research and prototyping processes often use contact or proximity lithography, because it uses inexpensive hardware and can achieve high optical resolution.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The resolution in proximity lithography is approximately the square root of the product of the wavelength and the gap distance.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Hence, except for projection lithography (see below), contact printing offers the best resolution, because its gap distance is approximately zero (neglecting the thickness of the photoresist itself).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In addition, nanoimprint lithography may revive interest in this familiar technique, especially since the cost of ownership is expected to be low; however, the shortcomings of contact printing discussed above remain as challenges.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Very-large-scale integration (VLSI) lithography uses projection systems.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Unlike contact or proximity masks, which cover an entire wafer, projection masks (known as "reticles") show only one die or an array of dies (known as a "field") in a portion of the wafer at a time.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Projection exposure systems (steppers or scanners) project the mask onto the wafer many times, changing the position of the wafer with every projection, to create the complete pattern, fully patterning the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The difference between steppers and scanners is that, during exposure, a scanner moves the photomask and the wafer simultaneously, while a stepper only moves the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Contact, proximity and projection Mask aligners preceded steppers and do not move the photomask nor the wafer during exposure and use masks that cover the entire wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Immersion lithography scanners use a layer of Ultrapure water between the lens and the wafer to increase resolution.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] An alternative to photolithography is nanoimprint lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The maximum size of the image that can be projected onto a wafer is known as the reticle limit.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The image for the mask originates from a computerized data file.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This data file is converted to a series of polygons and written onto a square of fused quartz substrate covered with a layer of chromium using a photolithographic process.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] A laser beam (laser writer) or a beam of electrons (e-beam writer) is used to expose the pattern defined by the data file and travels over the surface of the substrate in either a vector or raster scan manner.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Where the photoresist on the mask is exposed, the chrome can be etched away, leaving a clear path for the illumination light in the stepper/scanner system to travel through.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The ability to project a clear image of a small feature onto the wafer is limited by the wavelength of the light that is used, and the ability of the reduction lens system to capture enough diffraction orders from the illuminated mask.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Current state-of-the-art photolithography tools use deep ultraviolet (DUV) light from excimer lasers with wavelengths of 248 (KrF) and 193 (ArF) nm (the dominant lithography technology today is thus also called "**excimer laser lithography**"), which allow minimum feature sizes down to **50** nm.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Excimer laser lithography has thus played a critical role in the continued advance of the Moore's Law for the last 20 years (see below).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] where $\,CD$ is the **minimum feature size** (also called the **critical dimension**, **target design rule**, or "**half-pitch**"), $\,\lambda$ is the wavelength of light used, and $\,NA$ is the numerical aperture of the lens as seen from the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] $\,k_{1}$ (commonly called *k1 factor*) is a coefficient that encapsulates process-related factors and typically equals 0.4 for production.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] ( $\,k_{1}$ is actually a function of process factors such as the angle of incident light on a reticle and the incident light intensity distribution.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It is fixed per process.) The minimum feature size can be reduced by decreasing this coefficient through computational lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] According to this equation, minimum feature sizes can be decreased by decreasing the wavelength, and increasing the numerical aperture (to achieve a tighter focused beam and a smaller spot size).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] However, this design method runs into a competing constraint.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Here, $\,k_{2}$ is another process-related coefficient.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The depth of focus restricts the thickness of the photoresist and the depth of the topography on the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Chemical mechanical polishing is often used to flatten topography before high-resolution lithographic steps.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] From classical optics, k1=0.61 by the Rayleigh criterion.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The image of two points separated by less than 1.22 wavelength/NA will not maintain that separation but will be larger due to the interference between the Airy discs of the two points.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] It must also be remembered, though, that the distance between two features can also change with defocus.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Resolution is also nontrivial in a two-dimensional context.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] For example, a tighter line pitch results in wider gaps (in the perpendicular direction) between the ends of the lines.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] More fundamentally, straight edges become rounded for shortened rectangular features, where both x and y pitches are near the resolution limit.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] For advanced nodes, blur, rather than wavelength, becomes the key resolution-limiting factor.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Minimum pitch is given by blur sigma/0.14.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Blur is affected by dose as well as quantum yield, leading to a tradeoff with stochastic defects, in the case of EUV.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Besides resolution, depth of focus (DoF) is another key metric in lithography systems.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Depth of focus is inversely proportional to the square of the numerical aperture (NA) in projection lithography systems.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Periodic structures may be illuminated to greatly enhance depth of focus, e.g., two-beam imaging for fixed line pitch.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] On the other hand, non-periodic features like tip-to-tip gaps can severely limit depth of focus, limiting how much they can be shrunk; this effectively limits the resolution more than the minimum pitch.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] As light consists of photons, at low doses the image quality ultimately depends on the photon number.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This affects the use of extreme ultraviolet lithography or EUVL, which is limited to the use of low doses on the order of 20 photons/nm2.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This is due to fewer photons for the same energy dose for a shorter wavelength (higher energy per photon).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] With fewer photons making up the image, there is noise in the edge placement.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The stochastic effects would become more complicated with larger pitch patterns with more diffraction orders and using more illumination source points.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Secondary electrons in EUV lithography aggravate the stochastic characteristics.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Historically, photolithography has used ultraviolet light from gas-discharge lamps using mercury, sometimes in combination with noble gases such as xenon.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] These lamps produce light across a broad spectrum with several strong peaks in the ultraviolet range.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This spectrum is filtered to select a single spectral line.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] From the early 1960s through the mid-1980s, Hg lamps had been used in lithography for their spectral lines at 436 nm ("g-line"), 405 nm ("h-line") and 365 nm ("i-line").
[src:photolithography/photolithography] However, with the semiconductor industry's need for both higher resolution (to produce denser and faster chips) and higher throughput (for lower costs), lamp-based lithography tools were no longer able to meet the industry's high-end requirements.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This challenge was overcome in 1982 when excimer laser lithography was proposed and demonstrated at IBM by Kanti Jain.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Excimer laser lithography machines (steppers and scanners) became the primary tools in microelectronics production, and has enabled minimum features sizes in chip manufacturing to shrink from 800 nanometers in 1990 to 7 nanometers in 2018.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] From an even broader scientific and technological perspective, in the 50-year history of the laser since its first demonstration in 1960, the invention and development of excimer laser lithography has been recognized as a major milestone.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The commonly used deep ultraviolet excimer lasers in lithography systems are the krypton fluoride (KrF) laser at 248 nm wavelength and the argon fluoride laser (ArF) at 193 nm wavelength.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The primary manufacturers of excimer laser light sources in the 1980s were Lambda Physik (now part of Coherent, Inc.) and Lumonics.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Since the mid-1990s Cymer Inc. has become the dominant supplier of excimer laser sources to the lithography equipment manufacturers, with Gigaphoton Inc. as their closest rival.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Generally, an excimer laser is designed to operate with a specific gas mixture; therefore, changing wavelength is not a trivial matter, as the method of generating the new wavelength is completely different, and the absorption characteristics of materials change.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] For example, air begins to absorb significantly around the 193 nm wavelength; moving to sub-193 nm wavelengths would require installing vacuum pump and purge equipment on the lithography tools (a significant challenge).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] An inert gas atmosphere can sometimes be used as a substitute for a vacuum, to avoid the need for hard plumbing.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Furthermore, insulating materials such as silicon dioxide, when exposed to photons with energy greater than the band gap, release free electrons and holes which subsequently cause adverse charging.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Optical lithography has been extended to feature sizes below 50 nm using the 193 nm ArF excimer laser and liquid immersion techniques.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Also termed immersion lithography, this enables the use of optics with numerical apertures exceeding 1.0.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The liquid used is typically ultra-pure, deionised water, which provides for a refractive index above that of the usual air gap between the lens and the wafer surface.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The water is continually circulated to eliminate thermally-induced distortions.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Water will only allow *NA'*s of up to ~1.4, but fluids with higher refractive indices would allow the effective *NA* to be increased further.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Experimental tools using the 157 nm wavelength from the F2 excimer laser in a manner similar to current exposure systems have been built.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] These were once targeted to succeed 193 nm lithography at the 65 nm feature size node but have now all but been eliminated by the introduction of immersion lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This was due to persistent technical problems with the 157 nm technology and economic considerations that provided strong incentives for the continued use of 193 nm excimer laser lithography technology.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] High-index immersion lithography is the newest extension of 193 nm lithography to be considered.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 2006, features less than 30 nm were demonstrated by IBM using this technique.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] These systems used CaF2 calcium fluoride lenses.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Immersion lithography at 157 nm was explored.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] UV excimer lasers have been demonstrated to about 126 nm (for Ar2*).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Mercury arc lamps are designed to maintain a steady DC current of 50 to 150 Volts, however excimer lasers have a higher resolution.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Excimer lasers are gas-based light systems that are usually filled with inert and halide gases (Kr, Ar, Xe, F and Cl) that are charged by an electric field.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The higher the frequency, the greater the resolution of the image.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] KrF lasers are able to function at a frequency of 4 kHz .
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In addition to running at a higher frequency, excimer lasers are compatible with more advanced machines than mercury arc lamps are.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] They are also able to operate from greater distances (up to 25 meters) and are able to maintain their accuracy with a series of mirrors and antireflective-coated lenses.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] By setting up multiple lasers and mirrors, the amount of energy loss is minimized, also since the lenses are coated with antireflective material, the light intensity remains relatively the same from when it left the laser to when it hits the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Lasers have been used to indirectly generate non-coherent extreme UV (EUV) light at 13.5 nm for extreme ultraviolet lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] The EUV light is not emitted by the laser, but rather by a tin or xenon plasma which is excited by an excimer or CO2 laser.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] This technique does not require a synchrotron, and EUV sources, as noted, do not produce coherent light.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] However vacuum systems and a number of novel technologies (including much higher EUV energies than are now produced) are needed to work with UV at the edge of the X-ray spectrum (which begins at 10 nm).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] As of 2020, EUV is in mass production use by leading edge foundries such as TSMC and Samsung.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Theoretically, an alternative light source for photolithography, especially if and when wavelengths continue to decrease to extreme UV or X-ray, is the free-electron laser (or one might say xaser for an X-ray device).
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Free-electron lasers can produce high quality beams at arbitrary wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Visible and infrared femtosecond lasers were also applied for lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In that case photochemical reactions are initiated by multiphoton absorption.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Usage of these light sources have a lot of benefits, including possibility to manufacture true 3D objects and process non-photosensitized (pure) glass-like materials with superb optical resiliency.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Photolithography has been defeating predictions of its demise for many years.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] For instance, by the early 1980s, many in the semiconductor industry had come to believe that features smaller than 1 micron could not be printed optically.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Modern techniques using excimer laser lithography already print features with dimensions a fraction of the wavelength of light used – an amazing optical feat.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] New techniques such as immersion lithography, dual-tone resist and multiple patterning continue to improve the resolution of 193 nm lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Meanwhile, current research is exploring alternatives to conventional UV, such as electron beam lithography, X-ray lithography, extreme ultraviolet lithography and ion projection lithography.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Extreme ultraviolet lithography has entered mass production use, as of 2018 by Samsung and other manufacturers have followed suit.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] Electron beam lithography is only used in niche applications such as photomask production.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 2001 NIST publication has reported that photolithography process constituted about 35% of total cost of a wafer processing costs.
[src:photolithography/photolithography] In 2021, the photolithography industry was valued over 8 billion USD.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A **photomask** (also simply called a **mask**) is an opaque plate with transparent areas that allow light to shine through in a defined pattern.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Photomasks are commonly used in photolithography for the production of integrated circuits (ICs or "chips") to produce a pattern on a thin wafer of material (usually silicon).
[src:photolithography/photomask] In semiconductor manufacturing, a mask is sometimes called a **reticle**.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In photolithography, several masks are used in turn, each one reproducing a layer of the completed design, and together known as a **mask set**.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A curvilinear photomask has patterns with curves, which is a departure from conventional photomasks which only have patterns that are completely vertical or horizontal, known as manhattan geometry.
[src:photolithography/photomask] These photomasks require special equipment to manufacture.
[src:photolithography/photomask] For IC production in the 1960s and early 1970s, an opaque rubylith film laminated onto a transparent mylar sheet was used.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The design of one layer was cut into the rubylith, initially by hand on an illuminated drafting table (later by machine (plotter)) and the unwanted rubylith was peeled off by hand, forming the master image of that layer of the chip, often called "artwork".
[src:photolithography/photomask] At this point the master image could be arrayed into a multi-chip image called a ***reticle***.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The reticle was originally a 10X larger image of a single chip.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The reticle was, by step-and-repeater photolithography and etching, used to produce a photomask with an image size the same as the final chip.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The photomask might be used directly in the fab or be used as a master-photomask to produce the final actual working photomasks.
[src:photolithography/photomask] As feature size shrank, the only way to properly focus the image was to place it in direct contact with the wafer.
[src:photolithography/photomask] These contact aligners often lifted some of the photoresist off the wafer and onto the photomask and it had to be cleaned or discarded.
[src:photolithography/photomask] This drove the adoption of reverse master photomasks (see above), which were used to produce (with contact photolithography and etching) the needed many actual working photomasks.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Later, projection photo-lithography meant photomask lifetime was indefinite.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Still later direct-step-on-wafer *stepper* photo-lithography used reticles directly and ended the use of photomasks.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Initially soda glass was used with silver halide opacity.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Later borosilicate and then fused silica to control expansion, and chromium which has better opacity to ultraviolet light were introduced.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The original pattern generators have since been replaced by electron beam lithography and laser-driven mask writer or maskless lithography systems which generate reticles directly from the original computerized design.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Lithographic photomasks are typically transparent fused silica plates covered with a pattern defined with a chromium (Cr) or Fe2O3 metal absorbing film.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Photomasks are used at wavelengths of 365 nm, 248 nm, and 193 nm.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Photomasks have also been developed for other forms of radiation such as 157 nm, 13.5 nm (EUV), X-ray, electrons, and ions; but these require entirely new materials for the substrate and the pattern film.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A set of photomasks, each defining a pattern layer in integrated circuit fabrication, is fed into a photolithography stepper or scanner, and individually selected for exposure.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In multi-patterning techniques, a photomask would correspond to a subset of the layer pattern.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Historically in photolithography for the mass production of integrated circuit devices, there was a distinction between the term **photoreticle** or simply **reticle**, and the term **photomask**.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In the case of a photomask, there is a one-to-one correspondence between the mask pattern and the wafer pattern.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The mask covered the entire surface of the wafer which was exposed in its entirety in one shot.
[src:photolithography/photomask] This was the standard for the 1:1 mask aligners that were succeeded by steppers and scanners with reduction optics.
[src:photolithography/photomask] As used in steppers and scanners which use image projection, the reticle commonly contains only one copy, also called one layer of the designed VLSI circuit.
[src:photolithography/photomask] (However, some photolithography fabrications utilize reticles with more than one layer placed side by side onto the same mask, used as copies to create several identical integrated circuits from one photomask).
[src:photolithography/photomask] In modern usage, the terms reticle and photomask are synonymous.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In a modern stepper or scanner, the pattern in the photomask is projected and shrunk by four or five times onto the wafer surface.
[src:photolithography/photomask] To achieve complete wafer coverage, the wafer is repeatedly "stepped" from position to position under the optical column or the stepper lens until full exposure of the wafer is achieved.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A photomask with several copies of the integrated circuit design is used to reduce the number of steppings required to expose the entire wafer, thus increasing productivity.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Features 150 nm or below in size generally require phase-shifting to enhance the image quality to acceptable values.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The two most common methods are to use an attenuated phase-shifting background film on the mask to increase the contrast of small intensity peaks, or to etch the exposed quartz so that the edge between the etched and unetched areas can be used to image nearly zero intensity.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In the second case, unwanted edges would need to be trimmed out with another exposure.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The former method is *attenuated phase-shifting*, and is often considered a weak enhancement, requiring special illumination for the most enhancement, while the latter method is known as *alternating-aperture phase-shifting*, and is the most popular strong enhancement technique.
[src:photolithography/photomask] As leading-edge semiconductor features shrink, photomask features that are 4× larger must inevitably shrink as well.
[src:photolithography/photomask] This could pose challenges since the absorber film will need to become thinner, and hence less opaque.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A 2005 study by IMEC found that thinner absorbers degrade image contrast and therefore contribute to line-edge roughness, using state-of-the-art photolithography tools.
[src:photolithography/photomask] One possibility is to eliminate absorbers altogether and use "chromeless" masks, relying solely on phase-shifting for imaging.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The emergence of immersion lithography has a strong impact on photomask requirements.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The commonly used attenuated phase-shifting mask is more sensitive to the higher incidence angles applied in "hyper-NA" lithography, due to the longer optical path through the patterned film.
[src:photolithography/photomask] During manufacturing, inspection using a special form of microscopy called CD-SEM (Critical-Dimension Scanning Electron Microscopy) is used to measure critical dimensions on photomasks which are the dimensions of the patterns on a photomask.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Leading-edge photomasks (pre-corrected) images of the final chip patterns are magnified by four times.
[src:photolithography/photomask] This magnification factor has been a key benefit in reducing pattern sensitivity to imaging errors.
[src:photolithography/photomask] For example, a 25 nm wafer pattern should correspond to a 100 nm mask pattern, but the wafer tolerance could be 1.25 nm (5% spec), which translates into 5 nm on the photomask.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The variation of electron beam scattering in directly writing the photomask pattern can easily well exceed this.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The term "pellicle" is used to mean "film", "thin film", or "membrane." Beginning in the 1960s, thin film stretched on a metal frame, also known as a "pellicle", was used as a beam splitter for optical instruments.
[src:photolithography/photomask] It has been used in a number of instruments to split a beam of light without causing an optical path shift due to its small film thickness.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In 1978, Shea et al. at IBM patented a process to use the "pellicle" as a dust cover to protect a photomask or reticle.
[src:photolithography/photomask] In the context of this entry, "pellicle" means "thin film dust cover to protect a photomask".
[src:photolithography/photomask] Particle contamination can be a significant problem in semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:photolithography/photomask] A photomask is protected from particles by a pellicle – a thin transparent film stretched over a frame that is glued over one side of the photomask.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The pellicle is far enough away from the mask patterns so that moderate-to-small sized particles that land on the pellicle will be too far out of focus to print.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Although they are designed to keep particles away, pellicles become a part of the imaging system and their optical properties need to be taken into account.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Pellicles material are nitrocellulose and made for various transmission wavelengths.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Current pellicles are made from polysilicon, and companies are exploring other materials for high-NA EUV, such as CNT (carbon nanotubes), and future chip making processes.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The SPIE Annual Conference, Photomask Technology reports the SEMATECH Mask Industry Assessment which includes current industry analysis and the results of their annual photomask manufacturers survey.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Major chipmakers such as Intel, Globalfoundries, IBM, NEC, TSMC, UMC, Samsung, and Micron Technology, have their own large maskmaking facilities or joint ventures with the abovementioned companies.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The worldwide photomask market was estimated as $3.2 billion in 2012 and $3.1 billion in 2013.
[src:photolithography/photomask] Almost half of the market was from captive mask shops (in-house mask shops of major chipmakers).
[src:photolithography/photomask] The costs of creating new mask shop for 180 nm processes were estimated in 2005 as $40 million, and for 130 nm - more than $100 million.
[src:photolithography/photomask] The purchase price of a photomask, in 2006, could range from $250 to $100,000 for a single high-end phase-shift mask.
[src:photolithography/photomask] As many as 30 masks (of varying price) may be required to form a complete mask set.
[src:photolithography/photomask] As modern chips are built in several layers stacked on top of each other, at least one mask is required for each of these layers.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A **photoresist** (also known simply as a **resist**) is a light-sensitive material used in several processes, such as photolithography and photoengraving, to form a patterned coating on a surface.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] This process is crucial in the electronics industry.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The photoengraving process begins by coating a substrate with a light-sensitive organic material.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A patterned mask is then applied to the surface to block light, so that only unmasked regions of the material will be exposed to light.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A solvent, called a developer, is then applied to the surface.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] In the case of a positive photoresist, the photo-sensitive material is degraded by light, and the developer will dissolve away the regions that were exposed to light, leaving behind a coating where the mask was placed.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] In the case of a negative photoresist, the photosensitive material is strengthened (either polymerized or cross-linked) by light, and the developer will dissolve away only the regions that were not exposed to light, leaving behind a coating in areas where the mask was not placed.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A BARC (bottom anti-reflectant coating) may be applied before the photoresist is applied, to avoid reflections from occurring under the photoresist and to improve the photoresist's performance at smaller semiconductor nodes.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Conventional photoresists typically consist of 3 components: resin (a binder that provides physical properties such as adhesion, chemical resistance, etc), sensitizer (which has a photoactive compound), and solvent (which keeps the resist liquid).
[src:photolithography/photoresist] To explain this in graphical form, you may have a graph on Log exposure energy versus fraction of resist thickness remaining.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The positive resist will be completely removed at the final exposure energy, and the negative resist will be completely hardened and insoluble by the end of exposure energy.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The slope of this graph is the contrast ratio.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Intensity (I) is related to energy by E = I*t.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A *positive photoresist* is a type of photoresist in which a portion is exposed to light and becomes soluble to the photoresist developer.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The unexposed portion of the photoresist remains insoluble in the photoresist developer.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] A *negative photoresist* is a type of photoresist in which the portion of the photoresist that is exposed to light becomes insoluble in the photoresist developer.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The unexposed portion of the photoresist is dissolved by the photoresist developer.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] MTF (modulation transfer function is the ratio of image intensity modulation and object intensity modulation and it is a parameter that indicates the capability of an optical system.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The following table is based on generalizations which are generally accepted in the microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) fabrication industry.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Based on the chemical structure of photoresists, they can be classified into three types: photopolymeric, photodecomposing, and photocrosslinking photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] In lithography, decreasing the wavelength of light source is the most efficient way to achieve higher resolution.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Photoresists are most commonly used at wavelengths in the ultraviolet spectrum or shorter (<400 nm).
[src:photolithography/photoresist] For example, diazonaphthoquinone (DNQ) absorbs strongly from approximately 300 nm to 450 nm.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The absorption bands can be assigned to n-π* (S0–S1) and π-π* (S1–S2) transitions in the DNQ molecule.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] In the deep ultraviolet (DUV) spectrum, the π-π* electronic transition in benzene or carbon double-bond chromophores appears at around 200 nm.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Due to the appearance of more possible absorption transitions involving larger energy differences, the absorption tends to increase with shorter wavelength, or larger photon energy.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Photons with energies exceeding the ionization potential of the photoresist (can be as low as 5 eV in condensed solutions) can also release electrons which are capable of additional exposure of the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] From about 5 eV to about 20 eV, photoionization of outer "valence band" electrons is the main absorption mechanism.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Above 20 eV, inner electron ionization and Auger transitions become more important.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Photon absorption begins to decrease as the X-ray region is approached, as fewer Auger transitions between deep atomic levels are allowed for the higher photon energy.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The absorbed energy can drive further reactions and ultimately dissipates as heat.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] This is associated with the outgassing and contamination from the photoresist.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Photoresists can also be exposed by electron beams, producing the same results as exposure by light.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The main difference is that while photons are absorbed, depositing all their energy at once, electrons deposit their energy gradually, and scatter within the photoresist during this process.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] As with high-energy wavelengths, many transitions are excited by electron beams, and heating and outgassing are still a concern.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The dissociation energy for a C-C bond is 3.6 eV.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Secondary electrons generated by primary ionizing radiation have energies sufficient to dissociate this bond, causing scission.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The resulting scission breaks the original polymer into segments of lower molecular weight, which are more readily dissolved in a solvent, or else releases other chemical species (acids) which catalyze further scission reactions (see the discussion on chemically amplified resists below).
[src:photolithography/photoresist] It is not common to select photoresists for electron-beam exposure.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Electron beam lithography usually relies on resists dedicated specifically to electron-beam exposure.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Physical, chemical, and optical properties of photoresists influence their selection for different processes.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The primary properties of the photoresist are resolution capability, process dose and focus latitudes required for curing, and resistance to reactive ion etching.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Other key properties are sensitivity, compatibility with tetramethylammonium hydroxide (TMAH), adhesion, environmental stability, and shelf life.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Resolution is the ability to differ the neighboring features on the substrate.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Critical dimension (CD) is a main measure of resolution.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The smaller the CD is, the higher resolution would be.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Contrast is the difference from exposed portion to unexposed portion.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The higher the contrast is, the more obvious the difference between exposed and unexposed portions would be.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] The sensitivity of a photoresist is important when using deep ultraviolet (DUV) or extreme-ultraviolet (EUV).
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Viscosity is a measure of the internal friction of a fluid, affecting how easily it will flow.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] When it is needed to produce a thicker layer, a photoresist with higher viscosity will be preferred.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] Adherence is the adhesive strength between photoresist and substrate.
[src:photolithography/photoresist] If the resist comes off the substrate, some features will be missing or damaged.
